he work)", "explanation": ""}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 6, "excerpt": "Empirical Validation of the Contract Window (a structured record...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "A Contract Window is a shared document or data structure that tracks what a person and an AI system agree they're working on together, what has been confirmed as correct or completed, and who is assigned to fix any problems that arise. It creates accountability and clarity in human-AI collaboration."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 6, "excerpt": "Cognitive Governance Lab", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Cognitive Governance\"", "explanation": "Cognitive Governance refers to systematic methods for overseeing and managing how AI systems make decisions and interact with humans. It establishes rules, verification processes, and accountability structures to ensure AI systems operate reliably and transparently."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 15, "excerpt": "Evidence Basis: CONSTRUCTED \u2014 this plan is forward-looking.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"CONSTRUCTED \u2014 this plan is forward-looking\"", "explanation": "This plan describes research that has not yet been conducted; it is a roadmap of intended work rather than a report of completed experiments or findings. No actual results or data are being presented."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 14, "excerpt": "...on the Contract Window architecture for human-AI collaborative...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window architecture\"", "explanation": "This is a system design where humans and AI agree on explicit rules or 'contracts' at the start of their work together, and both parties check their behavior against those rules as they collaborate."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 18, "excerpt": "INVARIANT STATUS (whether the hard behavioral rules the AI committed to...)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"INVARIANT STATUS\"", "explanation": "This is a snapshot of which core promises or commitments the AI made at the beginning are still being kept; if an invariant is 'broken,' it means the AI violated one of its own rules."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 19, "excerpt": "...I2 active \u2014 no phantom work, deadlines are targets not achievements.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"phantom work\"", "explanation": "This means the AI will not pretend to have completed research tasks or make claims about findings that were never actually performed; instead, all deadlines are goals to aim for, not declarations that work is already done."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 21, "excerpt": "REPAIR OBLIGATIONS: None at plan initialization. Violations logged in...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"REPAIR OBLIGATIONS\"", "explanation": "These are debts or commitments the AI owes to fix past mistakes; logging violations means recording each time a rule was broken so it can be reviewed later."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 23, "excerpt": "CONSTRUCTED: Hypotheses H1, H2, H3 \u2014 derived from longitudinal observation...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"CONSTRUCTED\"", "explanation": "This label means the hypotheses were built from watching trends over time in the real world, not from running a controlled experiment, so they are less certain than experimentally tested claims."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 26, "excerpt": "...Whether n=30/condition (MVS) will replicate at n=60/condition.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"n=30/condition (MVS)\"", "explanation": "This refers to a test run with 30 participants in each group (n=30/condition) using a specific method called MVS; the question is whether the same results will hold when the test is repeated with twice as many participants (n=60)."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 52, "excerpt": "This is flagged per I2 \u2014 No Phantom Work. Do not plan 360 sessions...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"I2 \u2014 No Phantom Work\"", "explanation": "I2 is a governance rule that prohibits planning research as if you will magically complete unrealistic workloads; you must either reduce your study scope or extend your timeline to match actual human capacity."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 58, "excerpt": "the smallest sample size that gives adequate statistical power", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"statistical power\"", "explanation": "Statistical power is the probability that your study will correctly detect a real effect if one exists. Higher power means you're less likely to miss a true difference between your conditions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 63, "excerpt": "Two-sample t-test, two-tailed, \u03b1=0.05", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Two-sample t-test, two-tailed\"", "explanation": "A t-test is a statistical method that compares the average outcome between two groups to see if they differ significantly. 'Two-tailed' means you're testing whether one condition is either better or worse than the other, not just one direction."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 63, "excerpt": "Two-sample t-test, two-tailed, \u03b1=0.05", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"\u03b1=0.05\"", "explanation": "This is your significance threshold\u2014the probability of incorrectly declaring a difference exists when it doesn't. At 0.05, you accept a 5% risk of a false alarm."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 64, "excerpt": "Cohen's d=0.5 (medium effect): power \u2248 0.62", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Cohen's d\"", "explanation": "Cohen's d measures how large the difference between two conditions is in a standardized way. A d of 0.5 is considered a medium-sized difference, and 0.8 is large; bigger effect sizes are easier to detect."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 72, "excerpt": "a 38% chance of a false negative", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"false negative\"", "explanation": "A false negative means your study fails to detect a real difference that actually exists\u2014you conclude there's no effect when there genuinely is one."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 79, "excerpt": "If the effect size is large (d\u22650.8)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"effect size\"", "explanation": "Effect size describes how much impact your intervention has. Larger effects are easier to detect with smaller sample sizes, while tiny effects require more data to spot reliably."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 80, "excerpt": "it addresses a structural failure mode, not a marginal one", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"structural failure mode\"", "explanation": "A structural failure mode is a fundamental, widespread problem with how something works, rather than a minor edge case or small inefficiency."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 105, "excerpt": "Insight Atrophy (the gradual erosion of a person's ability to question AI outputs, caused by repeated exposure to fluent", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Insight Atrophy (IAI)\"", "explanation": "This is already well-explained in the parenthetical definition\u2014no flag needed."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 113, "excerpt": "Operationalize IAI as a composite of three observable turn-level signals", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"operationalize\"", "explanation": "While 'operationalize' is a research term, it should be followed by: 'This means converting the abstract concept into measurable, observable behaviors that can be consistently tracked and scored.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 114, "excerpt": "Operationalize IAI as a composite of three observable turn-level signals", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"turn-level signals\"", "explanation": "Should clarify: 'A turn-level signal is a measurable behavior or outcome observed during a single exchange between the human and the AI model.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 115, "excerpt": "1. Hypothesis generation rate \u2014 number of competing hypotheses surfaced per 10 turns", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Hypothesis generation rate\"", "explanation": "The definition given ('number of competing hypotheses surfaced per 10 turns') is operational but doesn't explain why this matters or what 'competing hypotheses' means in plain terms. Suggest: 'This counts how often the human proposes alternative explanations or questions whether the AI's answer is the only possibility.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 116, "excerpt": "2. Challenge rate \u2014 number of times human explicitly contests model output vs accepts without interrogation", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Challenge rate\"", "explanation": "The definition is clear enough, but 'interrogation' is slightly jargon-heavy. Consider: 'This measures how often the human pushes back on or questions the AI's answer, versus simply accepting it and moving on.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 117, "excerpt": "3. Scope contraction \u2014 whether the human's question set narrows or expands across session thirds", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Scope contraction\"", "explanation": "Unclear what 'scope' means here without further explanation. Should add: 'This tracks whether the range of topics and types of questions the human asks gets narrower or wider as the session progresses\u2014narrowing could indicate reduced curiosity or engagement.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 121, "excerpt": "These three signals can be extracted from transcripts by a blinded rater using a rubric.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"blinded rater\"", "explanation": "Should explain: 'A blinded rater is a person who scores the transcripts without knowing which experimental condition (1-6) the session belonged to, to avoid unconscious bias.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 122, "excerpt": "The IAI score is a weighted composite.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"weighted composite\"", "explanation": "Should add: 'A weighted composite combines the three signals into a single score by giving each one a different importance or 'weight' based on how much each contributes to the final IAI measurement.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 127, "excerpt": "H1 depends on intent-drift incident rate. The rubric needs to exist before pilot sessions. Draft the rubric: a turn is a", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"intent-drift incident\"", "explanation": "The term 'intent-drift incident' is introduced but not defined upfront before being used in 'H1 depends on intent-drift incident rate.' Should clarify before that line: 'An intent-drift incident occurs when the AI model shifts focus away from what the human actually wanted to explore.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 128, "excerpt": "the model's output addresses a goal that deviates from the Task State field by \u22652 points", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Task State field\"", "explanation": "Should explain: 'The Task State field is a record of what the human is currently trying to accomplish, allowing us to detect when the AI's output goes off-track from that goal.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 128, "excerpt": "on a 5-point alignment scale, scored by blinded rater", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"5-point alignment scale\"", "explanation": "Should clarify what the scale measures: 'This scale ranges from 1 (completely off-topic) to 5 (perfectly on-topic), measuring how closely the AI's response stays focused on what the human was actually asking.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 138, "excerpt": "ContractWindow state snapshot at each turn (JSON export from contract_window.py \u2014 this method already exists: to_json())", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"ContractWindow\"", "explanation": "While referenced as an existing method, 'ContractWindow' is not explained. Should add: 'ContractWindow is a system component that tracks constraints or boundaries applied to the AI model during each turn.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 139, "excerpt": "BicameralReview pass/fail per turn (from bicameral_review.py)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"BicameralReview\"", "explanation": "Should explain: 'BicameralReview is a safety or quality-check system that evaluates whether each AI model output meets certain standards, flagging it as a pass or fail.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 144, "excerpt": "Build the recorder as a thin wrapper around existing ContractWindow and BicameralReview classes.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"thin wrapper\"", "explanation": "Should clarify: 'A thin wrapper is a lightweight layer of new code that collects output from existing systems without duplicating or rewriting their core logic.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 153, "excerpt": "It wraps ContractWindow, calls BicameralReview, writes JSONL.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"ContractWindow\"", "explanation": "ContractWindow is a software component that manages a bounded interaction session\u2014it controls what inputs are allowed and what outputs can occur during a single conversation turn."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 153, "excerpt": "It wraps ContractWindow, calls BicameralReview, writes JSONL.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"BicameralReview\"", "explanation": "BicameralReview is a governance check that requires approval from two independent review processes before certain actions proceed, similar to how a legislature requires two chambers to pass a law."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 153, "excerpt": "It wraps ContractWindow, calls BicameralReview, writes JSONL.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"JSONL\"", "explanation": "JSONL is a file format where each line contains one complete JSON object; it makes it easy to stream and append data without rewriting the entire file."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 172, "excerpt": "check_comprehension_grade(text) \u2192 Flesch-Kincaid (a readability score...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Flesch-Kincaid Grade Level\"", "explanation": "The Flesch-Kincaid Grade Level is a numerical readability metric that estimates the U.S. school grade level needed to understand a piece of text; a score of 8 means an average 8th-grader should be able to comprehend it."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 175, "excerpt": "check_task_state_alignment(turn_text, task_state) \u2192 alignment score 1-5", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"alignment score 1-5\"", "explanation": "An alignment score of 1-5 is a numerical rating where higher numbers indicate that the model's response better matches the current state and requirements of the task."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 178, "excerpt": "Required columns: session_id, condition, turn_count, token_count, drift_incidents...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"drift_incidents\"", "explanation": "Drift_incidents refers to moments in a conversation when the model's behavior or outputs noticeably shift away from its intended guidelines or task focus."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 178, "excerpt": "Required columns: session_id, condition, turn_count, token_count, drift_incidents, repairs, ia_score, fk_grade.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"ia_score\"", "explanation": "ia_score is a summary metric (likely standing for 'interaction alignment score') that measures how well the model stayed on task and within its governance boundaries across an entire session."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 194, "excerpt": "2 sessions per condition for conditions 1-5. Skip condition 6", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"conditions 1-5 and condition 6 (combined)\"", "explanation": "The document refers to different experimental conditions (labeled 1 through 6) but never explains what distinguishes them or what they test. You need to know: what variable or intervention is being manipulated across these conditions, and why condition 6 is called 'combined' and is more complex to score."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 197, "excerpt": "Log cognitive load state before each session (high/medium/low) \u2014 this is both self-care and a covariate.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"covariate\"", "explanation": "A covariate is a background factor that can influence your results and that you want to track separately, so you can account for it later when analyzing whether the main thing you're testing actually made a difference. Here, logging your own cognitive load lets you check whether your fatigue (rather than the condition itself) affected your scoring."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 202, "excerpt": "Score all sessions with IAI rubric and drift rubric within 24 hours", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"IAI rubric and drift rubric\"", "explanation": "The document mentions two separate scoring tools (rubrics) but does not explain what each one measures or why both are needed. You need to know what 'IAI' stands for, what it evaluates, and what 'drift' means in this context."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 222, "excerpt": "Calculate Cohen's kappa (a statistical measure of agreement...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Cohen's kappa\"", "explanation": "Cohen's kappa is already explained in the parenthetical gloss provided in the document. No flag needed."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 229, "excerpt": "Use the 10 pilot sessions to estimate the correlation between each IAI component...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"IAI component (hypothesis rate, challenge rate, scope contraction)\"", "explanation": "IAI is introduced with three specific components listed, but 'IAI' itself is never defined. The reader does not know what IAI stands for or why these three specific measurements represent it. You should explain: 'IAI is a composite scoring system that measures three dimensions of how an AI system approaches problems: how often it generates new explanations, how often it questions its own reasoning, and how much it narrows the scope of what it's examining.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 232, "excerpt": "Weight the composite based on predictive validity, not intuition.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"predictive validity\"", "explanation": "Predictive validity is mentioned as the criterion for weighting but is never defined. You should explain: 'Predictive validity means how well each component actually predicts whether drift incidents will occur in practice, based on the pilot data.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 236, "excerpt": "Session recorder produces complete, parseable JSONL for all 6 conditions", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"JSONL\"", "explanation": "JSONL is mentioned as an output format but never explained. You should add: 'JSONL is a file format where each line contains one complete data record in JSON (a machine-readable structured format), making it easy for automated systems to read and process.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 237, "excerpt": "Invariant checkers produce numeric outputs without errors", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Invariant checkers\"", "explanation": "Invariant checkers are mentioned without explanation of what they check for or why. You should explain: 'Invariant checkers are automated tools that verify that certain conditions remain true throughout the data collection\u2014for example, ensuring that session IDs are consistent or that numerical scores stay within valid ranges.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 261, "excerpt": "Run the full minimum viable sample. 180 sessions, 30 per condition.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"minimum viable sample\"", "explanation": "This is the smallest number of research participants and observations needed to reliably answer your core research question. In this case, you need 180 total sessions divided equally across 6 different experimental conditions (30 each) to have confidence in your results."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 270, "excerpt": "180 sessions / 22 working days = 8.2 sessions/day if you work every day.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"condition\"", "explanation": "A condition is one version of the experiment you're testing\u2014for example, one group of participants might use the AI system with feature A on, while another group uses it with feature A off. You need enough sessions in each condition to see if the differences between them are real or just random variation."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 285, "excerpt": "Interleave conditions daily to avoid temporal confounds", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"temporal confounds\"", "explanation": "Temporal confounds are factors that change over time and could unfairly affect your results\u2014like your mental sharpness declining as the day goes on, or the API becoming slower. By mixing up the order of conditions instead of doing them one-by-one, you ensure that time-based changes don't systematically favor one condition over another."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 285, "excerpt": "avoid temporal confounds (your cognitive state, model API behavior changes)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"model API behavior changes\"", "explanation": "This refers to the possibility that the AI system you're testing may perform differently at different times\u2014for example, it might be slower during peak hours or produce slightly different outputs as its underlying software is updated. This variability could skew your results if you always test one condition at the same time of day."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 295, "excerpt": "Maintain /data/session-log.csv updated after every session", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"session_id\"", "explanation": "A unique identifier assigned to each individual conversation or interaction recorded in the study, used to link all data (audio, turns, tokens) belonging to that single participant session."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 295, "excerpt": "session_id, condition, date, duration_minutes, turn_count, token_count", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"condition\"", "explanation": "The experimental treatment or version the participant was assigned to (for example, if testing different AI systems or interfaces, this identifies which variant they used)."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 295, "excerpt": "session_id, condition, date, duration_minutes, turn_count, token_count", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"turn_count\"", "explanation": "The number of back-and-forth exchanges between the participant and the system\u2014each time the participant sends a message and receives a response counts as one turn."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 295, "excerpt": "session_id, condition, date, duration_minutes, turn_count, token_count", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"token_count\"", "explanation": "The total number of language units (roughly words or small word-pieces) processed by the AI system during the session; this measures computational complexity and cost."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 295, "excerpt": "turn_count, token_count, completion_status (COMPLETE/ABANDONED/PARTIAL), cognitive_load_pre_session", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"cognitive_load_pre_session\"", "explanation": "A measurement of how mentally taxed or tired the participant reported feeling before the session began, used to control for whether fatigue influenced their performance."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 299, "excerpt": "COMPLETE = \u226530 turns or \u226550K tokens, recorder functioned, no instrument failures", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"\u226530 turns or \u226550K tokens\"", "explanation": "Sessions qualify as COMPLETE if they meet at least one of two thresholds: either the participant completed at least 30 exchanges with the system, or the system processed at least 50,000 tokens; this ensures sufficient data was collected for analysis."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 302, "excerpt": "May be usable as a sensitivity check but not primary analysis", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"sensitivity check\"", "explanation": "A follow-up analysis that re-runs the main findings using slightly different data (in this case, PARTIAL sessions) to verify the results are robust and not dependent on exactly which sessions you include."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 329, "excerpt": "run 5-10 test prompts through a frontier model about Black consumer behavior", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"frontier model\"", "explanation": "A frontier model is one of the most advanced AI systems currently available\u2014essentially the state-of-the-art language model that represents the cutting edge of what's possible today. Testing against the newest model helps determine whether problems are inherent to all AI systems or specific to older versions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 330, "excerpt": "score the outputs against the Eight Wonders rubric", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Eight Wonders rubric\"", "explanation": "The Eight Wonders rubric is the evaluation framework being used in this project to assess and categorize the types of errors or biases that appear in the model's outputs. You should clarify what the rubric measures (e.g., does it score factual accuracy, bias categories, reasoning quality, or something else)."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 330, "excerpt": "This is the \"fluent wrong answer\" documentation the paper needs.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"fluent wrong answer\"", "explanation": "A fluent wrong answer is when an AI system generates output that sounds confident and well-reasoned but is actually incorrect or misleading. This is particularly dangerous because it convinces readers without signaling uncertainty."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 360, "excerpt": "Run data_pipeline.py on all sessions", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"data_pipeline.py\"", "explanation": "This is a computer script that processes raw video or audio recordings to extract the information needed for analysis. It likely removes duplicates, fills in missing pieces, and organizes everything into a standard format for the next step."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 368, "excerpt": "Score all sessions with drift rubric (if not scored during collection)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"drift rubric\"", "explanation": "A drift rubric is a checklist or scoring guide that measures how much a conversation, performance, or behavior moved away from its original direction or intent. In this study, it likely assesses whether participants' responses stayed consistent or drifted to different topics."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 369, "excerpt": "Score all sessions with IAI rubric", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"IAI rubric\"", "explanation": "The IAI rubric is the specific scoring guide you are using to measure whatever concept IAI represents; without knowing what IAI stands for in your study, readers cannot understand what dimension of the data is being measured or why it matters."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 370, "excerpt": "Confirm scorer does not know condition assignments during scoring (blind scoring).", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"blind scoring\"", "explanation": "Blind scoring means the person rating the recordings does not know which group (control, treatment A, treatment B, etc.) each session belongs to, so their judgments cannot be unconsciously biased by knowing what result is expected."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 372, "excerpt": "DV: intent-drift incident rate (incidents per 10 turns)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"intent-drift incident rate\"", "explanation": "This is a measurement of how often the AI system's responses start moving away from the user's original intent or goals during a conversation, counted as the number of such incidents that occur for every 10 user messages."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 375, "excerpt": "Effect size: Cohen's d", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Cohen's d\"", "explanation": "Cohen's d is a number that describes how big the practical difference is between two groups \u2014 a way to measure whether a statistically significant result is actually meaningful in the real world."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 376, "excerpt": "Claim threshold: \u226525% reduction, statistically significant at \u03b1=0.05", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"\u03b1=0.05\"", "explanation": "This is the threshold for statistical significance; it means we will only accept a result as reliable if there is less than a 5% chance it happened by random luck."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 384, "excerpt": "DV: drift repair rate (proportion of drift incidents resolved within 3 turns)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"drift repair rate\"", "explanation": "This measures how successful the system is at fixing cases where the conversation has drifted off-topic, specifically counting what fraction of drift incidents are corrected within the next 3 user messages."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 390, "excerpt": "DV: lay reader comprehension accuracy (% correct on session-state questions)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"lay reader comprehension accuracy\"", "explanation": "This is a test of how well ordinary people (not AI experts) can understand what the AI system is doing, measured by asking them questions about the conversation state and checking what percentage they answer correctly."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 391, "excerpt": "DV: lay reader comprehension accuracy (% correct on session-state questions)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"session-state questions\"", "explanation": "These are questions that ask a reader about the current state of the conversation \u2014 for example, what the user's goal was, or what the system was trying to do \u2014 to measure whether the system's behavior is transparent or confusing."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 392, "excerpt": "Material: CW render() output from session_recorder, formatted per protocol", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"CW render() output\"", "explanation": "This refers to the formatted, readable version of the system's output that is displayed to users or readers \u2014 the end product that shows what the system actually communicated."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 394, "excerpt": "Test: one-sample proportion test against 80% null", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"one-sample proportion test\"", "explanation": "This is a statistical test that checks whether a measured percentage (like comprehension accuracy) is meaningfully different from a target percentage (in this case, 80%)."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 409, "excerpt": "exclusions, power analysis for actual n", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"power analysis\"", "explanation": "A statistical calculation that determines whether your sample size was large enough to reliably detect the effect you're studying; it shows you didn't just get lucky with your results."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 411, "excerpt": "H1 results: effect size, CI, p-value, whether \u226525% threshold met", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"effect size\"", "explanation": "A number that measures how big the difference or relationship actually is between your conditions\u2014not just whether it's real, but how substantial it is."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 411, "excerpt": "H1 results: effect size, CI, p-value, whether \u226525% threshold met", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"CI\"", "explanation": "A range of numbers (confidence interval) that tells you where the true result probably lies\u2014for example, if your effect size is 0.5 with a CI of 0.3 to 0.7, the real value is likely somewhere in that band."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 411, "excerpt": "H1 results: effect size, CI, p-value, whether \u226525% threshold met", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"p-value\"", "explanation": "A number indicating how likely your result would occur by pure chance if there were actually no real effect; smaller p-values mean your finding is less likely to be a fluke."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 413, "excerpt": "H2 results: repair rate comparison, odds ratio, whether \u22652x threshold met", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"odds ratio\"", "explanation": "A number comparing how much more (or less) likely one outcome is versus another between two groups\u2014for example, an odds ratio of 2 means one group is twice as likely to have the outcome."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 415, "excerpt": "H3 results: comprehension accuracy, CI, whether \u226580% threshold met", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"comprehension accuracy\"", "explanation": "The percentage or proportion of questions or tasks that participants answered or completed correctly."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 416, "excerpt": "Secondary analysis: IAI scores across conditions, correlation with drift incident rate", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"IAI scores\"", "explanation": "Numerical measurements on the IAI scale; without knowing what IAI stands for earlier in the document, a reader cannot understand what is being measured."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 416, "excerpt": "Secondary analysis: IAI scores across conditions, correlation with drift incident rate", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"drift incident rate\"", "explanation": "The frequency or proportion of times a particular type of failure or problem (drift incidents) occurred; this matters because you're checking whether it correlates with the IAI scores."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 419, "excerpt": "grouped bar chart, drift incident rate by condition with 95% CIs", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"95% CIs\"", "explanation": "Confidence intervals set at the 95% level, meaning there is a 95% probability that the true value falls within the range shown by the error bars on the chart."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 424, "excerpt": "Formalize this as an appendix or supplementary analysis for the CW paper", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"CW paper\"", "explanation": "CW is an abbreviation; clarify what 'CW' stands for and what this paper is about (e.g., 'the Crowdworker Validation study' or 'the Content Moderation Warnings research')."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 430, "excerpt": "H1/H2/H3 each evaluated with a clear TRUE/FALSE/INCONCLUSIVE designation", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"H1/H2/H3\"", "explanation": "These appear to be hypothesis labels but the document never defines what H1, H2, and H3 are testing or why these three hypotheses matter to the research."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 459, "excerpt": "State the problem (Insight Atrophy, fluent wrong answers)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Insight Atrophy\"", "explanation": "Insight Atrophy is the phenomenon where an AI system produces answers that sound confident and fluent but are actually incorrect or misleading, causing users to lose the ability to recognize flaws in AI reasoning. This matters because users may trust AI outputs without proper verification, leading to bad decisions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 460, "excerpt": "State the contribution (Contract Window + 6 invariants)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window + 6 invariants\"", "explanation": "The Contract Window is a method or framework for controlling when and how an AI system provides responses, and the 6 invariants are specific rules or properties that must always hold true to ensure the system behaves reliably. Together they represent the proposed solution to the Insight Atrophy problem."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 462, "excerpt": "State the empirical claim (H1/H2/H3, now with actual results)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"H1/H2/H3\"", "explanation": "H1, H2, and H3 are three specific hypotheses (testable predictions) that the experiment is designed to evaluate. These are the measurable claims about how the Contract Window and invariants actually perform in practice."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 475, "excerpt": "Methods section: session protocol, condition specifications, instruments, blinding procedure, statistical tests.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"blinding procedure\"", "explanation": "A blinding procedure is a method where participants or researchers are kept unaware of which experimental condition (treatment or control) is being used, to prevent bias from influencing results. This ensures that expectations about the intervention do not unconsciously affect how people rate or respond to the system."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 474, "excerpt": "What the IAI score distribution tells you", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"IAI score distribution\"", "explanation": "IAI (Interpretability Alignment Index) is a numerical measurement of how well the model's outputs align with human expectations; the distribution refers to how these scores spread across your sample\u2014whether most scores cluster in one range or vary widely."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 480, "excerpt": "Single investigator as both experimenter and rater (partial blindness)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"partial blindness\"", "explanation": "This means you knew which condition each participant was in while rating their responses, so your ratings could have been unconsciously influenced by knowing the hypothesis or treatment group."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 481, "excerpt": "MVS (Minimum Viable Sample \u2014 the smallest sample size that gives adequate statistical power to detect a meaningful diffe", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"MVS (Minimum Viable Sample)\"", "explanation": "The parenthetical is present but incomplete for a lay reader; consider adding: 'At d=0.5 with n=30, your study would have roughly a 47% chance of detecting a real effect if one exists\u2014well below the standard 80% threshold, so if you find nothing, that may reflect your small sample rather than a true absence of effect.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 482, "excerpt": "Observational foundation of the invariant set", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Observational foundation of the invariant set\"", "explanation": "This limitation means your identification of which outputs count as reliable or stable (the 'invariant set') came from watching what happened in your data rather than from a pre-registered prediction, so you may have unconsciously included or excluded cases that fit your hypothesis."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 483, "excerpt": "Lay reader sample not probability-sampled", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"probability-sampled\"", "explanation": "Your lay readers were chosen by convenience (e.g., volunteers you recruited) rather than by random selection from the full population of possible lay readers, so they may differ systematically from the broader public in ways that affect your findings."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 503, "excerpt": "Run the paper through the Bicameral Review (two independent review channels...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Bicameral Review\"", "explanation": "A quality control process where two separate reviewers\u2014one checking whether the work answers the research question, and one checking for unfounded claims\u2014must both approve the output before it is shared. Neither reviewer can override the other's decision."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 503, "excerpt": "...does this introduce a phantom claim?", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"phantom claim\"", "explanation": "A claim presented as fact or supported by evidence when it is actually unsupported, unverified, or based on a misinterpretation of the data. Phantom claims mislead readers into accepting conclusions that the evidence does not justify."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 539, "excerpt": "Final V&T (Verification and Truth \u2014 a statement that explicitly...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"V&T (Verification and Truth)\"", "explanation": "This means you must explicitly state which claims in your paper are based on solid evidence (verified) and which are new ideas you're proposing (truth-claims). Every factual statement should be marked with where it comes from \u2014 your own experiments, published research, or your new argument."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 540, "excerpt": "Every empirical claim must be tagged with its evidence basis.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"empirical claim\"", "explanation": "An empirical claim is any statement about how the world actually works, based on observation or experiment \u2014 as opposed to pure logic or opinion. For example, 'our model achieved 87% accuracy' is empirical; 'we should prioritize safety' is not."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 531, "excerpt": "Submitting to a deadline you cannot meet is phantom work (I2).", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"phantom work (I2)\"", "explanation": "Phantom work means investing effort on a task that cannot possibly succeed \u2014 in this case, submitting to a conference deadline that has already passed. The reference 'I2' appears to be an internal indexing system; the core point is that you should avoid wasting time on impossible goals."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 579, "excerpt": "Instrument fails kappa gate in May", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"kappa gate\"", "explanation": "A kappa gate is a validation checkpoint that checks whether your measurement instrument (the tool you're using to collect data) is producing consistent and reliable results. If it fails, it means the instrument isn't working well enough to trust for your actual study."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 583, "excerpt": "Data collection falls short of n=30/condition", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"n=30/condition\"", "explanation": "This refers to collecting data from 30 participants in each separate group or condition of your study. If you fall short, you have fewer data points to analyze, which weakens your statistical conclusions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 585, "excerpt": "Lay reader recruitment fails for H3", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"H3\"", "explanation": "H3 is shorthand for your third hypothesis\u2014a specific prediction you're testing in the study. Lay readers are people without expert training who will help validate whether your findings make sense to non-specialists."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 587, "excerpt": "Analysis reveals instrument invalidity", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"instrument invalidity\"", "explanation": "Instrument invalidity means your measurement tool is not actually measuring what you intended it to measure, which would make all your results unreliable and unusable."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 589, "excerpt": "Pilot validation gate in May is the firewall", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"pilot validation gate\"", "explanation": "A pilot validation gate is a checkpoint where you test your instrument on a small sample before your main study to catch problems early. This acts as a firewall by preventing you from proceeding to the expensive main study if the instrument isn't working."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 649, "excerpt": "These are not preferences. They are constraints derived from I1-I6 and", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"I1-I6\"", "explanation": "I1-I6 refers to six foundational principles or investigator commitments that form the basis for these constraints; the reader needs to know what these six items are or where to find them to understand why these rules exist."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 656, "excerpt": "Do not run data collection sessions when cognitive load is HIGH.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"cognitive load is HIGH\"", "explanation": "This refers to a specific, measurable threshold of mental fatigue or distraction that has been defined elsewhere in the project; without knowing the operational definition or measurement, it is unclear when this rule applies."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 660, "excerpt": "Do not work on Frontin or Graves during active data collection weeks", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"active data collection weeks\"", "explanation": "This phrase implies there is a defined schedule distinguishing 'active data collection weeks' from other periods; the reader should know how this calendar or status is determined."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 660, "excerpt": "unless you are in a burst that does not touch the primary pipeline", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"burst that does not touch the primary pipeline\"", "explanation": "A 'burst' and 'primary pipeline' are terms that describe a specific workflow or scheduling pattern used in this project; their meaning should be clarified so the exception is actionable."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 663, "excerpt": "Do not work on Frontin or Graves during active data collection weeks", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Frontin or Graves\"", "explanation": "Frontin and Graves are referenced as separate work streams or projects; the reader should understand what these are and why they compete for attention with data collection."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 664, "excerpt": "replaced with MVS (Minimum Viable Sample \u2014 the smallest sample size that gives adequate statistical power to detect a me", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"MVS (Minimum Viable Sample)\"", "explanation": "While a definition is provided in parentheses, 'adequate statistical power' and 'meaningful difference' are themselves technical terms that a non-specialist may not understand; the plain-language version should explain that this is the smallest group size needed to reliably detect a real effect in the data."}], "status": "FIXED"}
{"timestamp": "2026-05-01T07:54:11.121840+00:00", "file": "/Users/coreyalejandro/cognitive-governance-lab/proposal/executive-summary-proposal.md", "violation_count": 118, "bmt1_count": 5, "bmt2_count": 113, "bmt4_count": 0, "violations": [{"requirement": "BMT-1", "line_number": 7, "excerpt": "**The Living Constitution (TLC)** is a runtime enforcement system built alongside this research \u2014 a ", "suggestion": "Define \"TLC\" on first use: TLC (The Living Constitution \u2014 the runtime enforcement system built alongside this research that applies constitutional rules to AI behavior session by session)", "explanation": ""}, {"requirement": "BMT-1", "line_number": 60, "excerpt": "- Which epistemic commitments are active and whether they have been violated (Invariant Status)", "suggestion": "Define \"Invariant Status\" on first use: Invariant Status (whether the hard behavioral rules the AI committed to at the start of the session are still being honored)", "explanation": ""}, {"requirement": "BMT-1", "line_number": 132, "excerpt": "Contract Window outputs formatted to accessibility-grade readability standards (Flesch-Kincaid Grade", "suggestion": "Define \"Flesch-Kincaid\" on first use: Flesch-Kincaid Grade Level (a readability score \u2014 Grade 8 means a typical 8th-grader can understand the text)", "explanation": ""}, {"requirement": "BMT-1", "line_number": 189, "excerpt": "Black women's health disparities, specifically Graves' disease. Narrative-first CRISP-DM (Cross-Indu", "suggestion": "Define \"CRISP-DM\" on first use: CRISP-DM (Cross-Industry Standard Process for Data Mining \u2014 a standard workflow for data analysis projects, from business understanding through deployment)", "explanation": ""}, {"requirement": "BMT-1", "line_number": 199, "excerpt": "### Scalable Oversight (a research area focused on how humans can supervise AI systems even when tho", "suggestion": "Define \"Scalable Oversight\" on first use: scalable oversight (a research area focused on how humans can supervise AI systems even when those systems become more capable than the humans overseeing them)", "explanation": ""}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 7, "excerpt": "Governing the Investigative Arc: A Contract Window", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Investigative Arc\"", "explanation": "An investigative arc is the sequence of steps a human and AI take together to explore a question or solve a problem, from the initial goal through verification of results. It describes the full journey of collaborative work."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 7, "excerpt": "A Contract Window (a structured record of what a human-AI session is trying to accomplish, what has been verified, and w", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "While a parenthetical is present, 'Contract Window' needs clarification on why it's called a 'window' and why the metaphor of a contract matters\u2014it should specify that it's a transparent, auditable boundary defining mutual obligations between human and AI."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 9, "excerpt": "Architecture for Cognitive Safety in Human-AI Collaboration", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Cognitive Safety\"", "explanation": "Cognitive safety refers to protecting human thinking and decision-making from being misled, manipulated, or corrupted by AI outputs or advice. It ensures humans can verify and trust what an AI tells them."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 15, "excerpt": "The Living Constitution (TLC) is a runtime enforcement system built alongside this research \u2014 a software layer that appl", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"constitutional rules\"", "explanation": "Constitutional rules are principles or constraints that govern how an AI system should behave, similar to how a constitution guides government\u2014they define what the AI is and is not allowed to do in each session."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 15, "excerpt": "a software layer that applies constitutional rules to AI behavior session by session", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"runtime enforcement\"", "explanation": "Runtime enforcement means the rules are checked and applied continuously while the AI is actually working, moment by moment, rather than being enforced only before or after the session ends."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 26, "excerpt": "I call this **Insight Atrophy (the gradual erosion of a person's ability to question AI outputs, caused by repeated expo", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Insight Atrophy\"", "explanation": "This is actually already defined in parentheses, but the definition itself contains an unexplained prerequisite: 'fluent but wrong answers' \u2014 answers that sound confident and well-written but are factually incorrect. The reader should understand why fluency (smoothness of language) makes the problem worse, not better."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 31, "excerpt": "It pattern-matches to adjacent surface features and produces outputs that are locally coherent, globally wrong...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"pattern-matches to adjacent surface features\"", "explanation": "This means the model recognizes features in the input that resemble patterns it has seen before, then generates output based on surface similarities rather than deep understanding \u2014 like recognizing keywords without grasping what the user actually needs."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 33, "excerpt": "...indistinguishable from correct answers without domain-specific interrogation.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"domain-specific interrogation\"", "explanation": "This refers to asking detailed, expert-level questions that require specialized knowledge in a particular field \u2014 the kind of scrutiny only someone trained in that area can apply."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 39, "excerpt": "That record is what I call the **Contract Window**.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "The term is introduced but not explained. Based on context, it appears to be a shared record between human and AI of their investigation's current state, but the executive summary does not spell out what that means operationally or why it is called a 'contract.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 42, "excerpt": "...operationalized through accessibility-grade runtime invariants...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"accessibility-grade runtime invariants\"", "explanation": "This phrase combines three unexplained terms. 'Runtime' means during active use; 'invariants' are rules that stay constant; 'accessibility-grade' is unclear \u2014 it may mean designed to be usable by people with disabilities, but that connection is not stated."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 43, "excerpt": "...statistically improves **Intent Fidelity (whether the AI is still serving the user's actual purpose, as opposed to dr", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Intent Fidelity\"", "explanation": "This is defined parenthetically, but 'drifting toward adjacent goals' is vague. The reader should understand: as a conversation progresses, the AI may subtly shift focus toward tasks that are close to, but not exactly, what the user asked for \u2014 and Intent Fidelity measures whether that drift is happening."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 37, "excerpt": "Standard AI safety evaluation asks: did the model produce a harmful output?", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"output-level evaluation\"", "explanation": "This means checking only whether the final answer the AI gives is harmful or not, without looking at how the AI arrived at that answer or what damage might occur indirectly."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 39, "excerpt": "There is a second-order failure mode that does not appear in output-level evaluation.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"second-order failure mode\"", "explanation": "This is a problem that doesn't show up when you just check if outputs are bad\u2014it's a harmful effect that happens one step removed from the obvious outputs."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 41, "excerpt": "They stop generating competing interpretations. They stop asking the questions that would surface the gap. The model has", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"hypothesis space contracts\"", "explanation": "The human's set of possible explanations for a problem shrinks, meaning they consider fewer alternative theories and stop exploring different possibilities."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 42, "excerpt": "The model has not hallucinated in the classical sense.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"hallucinated\"", "explanation": "In AI terminology, hallucination means the model invents false information that sounds plausible; here the author is distinguishing Insight Atrophy from that traditional error."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 47, "excerpt": "Long interactions (the model's framing accumulates and shapes the human's question-generation over time)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Long interactions\"", "explanation": "Extended back-and-forth conversations where the model's earlier answers bias how the human asks follow-up questions, making them less likely to challenge the model's framing."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 46, "excerpt": "The classical hallucination frame treats model errors as identifiable fabrications.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"hallucination frame\"", "explanation": "This refers to the standard way people think about AI mistakes\u2014as obvious, detectable errors or made-up information. The problem this section raises is that this frame misses a different, harder-to-spot kind of failure."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 47, "excerpt": "The more insidious failure mode is the structurally correct-sounding answer that is wrong in ways that are invisible wit", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"failure mode\"", "explanation": "A failure mode is a specific type of error or malfunction. In this case, it means the AI produces answers that sound reasonable and well-structured but are actually wrong in ways only an expert in that field would catch."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 50, "excerpt": "...behavior, language, or decision patterns operate through interpretive frameworks the model was not trained on.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"interpretive frameworks\"", "explanation": "This means the set of cultural assumptions, values, or mental models that a group uses to understand the world\u2014for example, different communities may interpret authority, time, or family relationships differently than what appeared in the model's training data."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 65, "excerpt": "It does not address runtime governance: the question of whether...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"runtime governance\"", "explanation": "Runtime governance means rules and oversight that apply while the AI is actively working with a user, moment-by-moment, rather than rules baked in during training. It's about checking whether the AI is staying on track for the specific task at hand."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 68, "excerpt": "What the investigation is and what it is trying to establish (Task State)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Task State\"", "explanation": "Task State is a record of what the investigation is supposed to accomplish and what specific claims or questions it is trying to answer. It serves as the reference point to check whether the AI is working toward the right goal."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 69, "excerpt": "Which epistemic commitments are active and whether they have been violated", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"epistemic commitments\"", "explanation": "Epistemic commitments are the factual or logical assumptions the investigation has agreed to treat as true or binding\u2014for example, 'we are assuming this document is authentic' or 'we have committed to the scientific method for testing this hypothesis.' Tracking them prevents the investigation from contradicting itself."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 69, "excerpt": "Which epistemic commitments are active and whether they have been violated (Invariant Status)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Invariant Status\"", "explanation": "Invariant Status is a record of which commitments remain in effect and whether any have been broken, so that violations can be detected and addressed rather than ignored."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 70, "excerpt": "What has broken and who bears the obligation to repair it (Repair Obligations)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Repair Obligations\"", "explanation": "Repair Obligations is a record of what has gone wrong\u2014such as a violated commitment or factual error\u2014and which party (the AI, the human investigator, or the data source) is responsible for fixing it. This prevents problems from being swept under the rug."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 71, "excerpt": "What has been verified, what is contested, what is unknown (Truth Status)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Truth Status\"", "explanation": "Truth Status is a classification of each claim or piece of evidence as either confirmed, disputed among the participants, or still unclear, so that the investigation can distinguish solid findings from remaining open questions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 73, "excerpt": "This four-field structure is the Contract Window.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "The Contract Window is the proposed name for a unified, visible record that displays all four fields together (Task State, Invariant Status, Repair Obligations, and Truth Status) so that both the human and the AI can monitor whether the investigation is staying true to its original terms and assumptions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 75, "excerpt": "It is a runtime artifact that both human and model can read", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"runtime artifact\"", "explanation": "A runtime artifact is information that exists and can be accessed during the actual execution of a conversation, rather than being set up beforehand or stored separately\u2014think of it like a shared notepad that stays visible throughout your entire interaction."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 76, "excerpt": "transforms the interaction from a request-response exchange into a governed investigative arc", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"governed investigative arc\"", "explanation": "This means the conversation follows a structured path with rules and checkpoints, rather than being a simple back-and-forth where each response stands alone."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 86, "excerpt": "Which epistemic commitments are active", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"epistemic commitments\"", "explanation": "Epistemic commitments are specific promises the AI makes about how it will reason, what it will and won't claim to know, and what logical rules it will follow during the conversation."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 89, "excerpt": "Verified / contested / unknown | Phantom confidence, invisible epistemic gaps", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Phantom confidence\"", "explanation": "Phantom confidence means the AI sounds certain about something when it actually has no solid basis for that certainty\u2014it's a trap where false confidence goes undetected."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 93, "excerpt": "It was co-designed with frontier AI systems.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"frontier AI systems\"", "explanation": "Frontier AI systems are the most advanced, cutting-edge AI models currently available\u2014systems operating at or near the current technological frontier."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 94, "excerpt": "what would a Level-5 intelligence entity \u2014 meaning a system operating at its highest possible capacity", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Level-5 intelligence entity\"", "explanation": "This phrase is already glossed in the text, so no additional explanation needed."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 96, "excerpt": "maintain coherence, fidelity, and safety", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"coherence, fidelity, and safety\"", "explanation": "Coherence means the AI's reasoning stays logically consistent; fidelity means it stays true to its stated commitments and constraints; safety means it avoids harmful outputs and maintains control."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 98, "excerpt": "are candidates for formal invariant status", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"formal invariant status\"", "explanation": "Formal invariant status means treating something as a permanent, non-negotiable rule that must be preserved throughout the entire system's operation, rather than as a suggestion or preference."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 89, "excerpt": "Does this output serve the investigative arc? Does it advance...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"investigative arc\"", "explanation": "The investigative arc is the thread of inquiry or line of questioning that the human is pursuing; serving it means the output moves that specific inquiry forward rather than distracting from it or making it harder to follow."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 90, "excerpt": "Does it introduce a phantom claim, a silent assumption, or...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"phantom claim\"", "explanation": "A phantom claim is a statement that sounds factual but has no real basis \u2014 it appears confident and coherent but is actually made up or unsupported by evidence."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 90, "excerpt": "Does it introduce a phantom claim, a silent assumption, or...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"silent assumption\"", "explanation": "A silent assumption is a premise the output takes for granted without stating it explicitly; the reader may not realize the output is built on an unproven or contestable foundation."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 90, "excerpt": "Does it introduce a phantom claim, a silent assumption, or fluent wrong answer?", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"fluent wrong answer\"", "explanation": "A fluent wrong answer is a response that reads smoothly and confidently but is factually incorrect; it sounds plausible and well-reasoned even though it is false."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 94, "excerpt": "It operationalizes the dual-newspaper test \u2014 a standard from...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"dual-newspaper test\"", "explanation": "The dual-newspaper test is a simple fairness check: would you be comfortable seeing this output printed in two major newspapers, one asking 'Is this harmful?' and one asking 'Is this needlessly unhelpful?' \u2014 both must answer 'no' for the output to pass."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 95, "excerpt": "...at the inference layer, per turn, with an auditable record.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"inference layer\"", "explanation": "The inference layer is the moment when the AI system generates and delivers its response to the user; checking at this layer means the review happens in real time, for each individual response, rather than after the fact."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 95, "excerpt": "[CONSTRUCTED \u2014 operationalized from longitudinal observation, pending formal experimental validation]", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"operationalized from longitudinal observation\"", "explanation": "This means the six rules were derived by watching how a system performed over time rather than being designed theoretically first. The authors observed patterns in real outputs and then formalized them into these six rules."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 97, "excerpt": "I1 \u2014 Evidence-First Outputs: Every claim tagged with its evidence basis", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Evidence-First Outputs with VERIFIED / CONSTRUCTED / PENDING tags\"", "explanation": "Each statement the system makes must be labeled to show where it came from: VERIFIED means it's backed by reliable data or sources, CONSTRUCTED means it was reasoned or inferred by the model, and PENDING means it hasn't been checked yet."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 98, "excerpt": "I2 \u2014 No Phantom Work: No performance claims without named methodology, baseline, and dataset", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Phantom Work\"", "explanation": "This term means claiming that something works well without actually explaining how it was tested, what it was compared against, or what data was used\u2014in other words, making impressive-sounding claims without proof."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 99, "excerpt": "I3 \u2014 Confidence Requires Verification: Hedged language is not a substitute for verification", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Hedged language as a substitute for verification\"", "explanation": "Hedged language means using cautious phrases like 'may possibly' or 'might potentially' to sound more careful; this invariant says that vague qualification alone does not count as real verification or proof."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 102, "excerpt": "I6 \u2014 Fail Closed: When in doubt, stop and flag \u2014 do not proceed", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Fail Closed\"", "explanation": "This is a safety principle meaning that if the system is uncertain whether something is correct or safe, it should stop and alert a human rather than make a guess and continue forward."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 108, "excerpt": "structured epistemic hygiene statement:", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"epistemic hygiene statement\"", "explanation": "This means a clearly marked statement that shows what information is reliable, what sources were checked, and what claims are NOT being made\u2014essentially a quality-control label for the accuracy and limits of the output."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 113, "excerpt": "frontier models (a state-of-the-art AI system at the edge of current capability)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"frontier models\"", "explanation": "This parenthetical gloss is present but uses technical language ('state-of-the-art', 'edge of current capability') that still may not clarify why these specific models matter for this observation; a plainer version: 'the most advanced AI systems available at the time of testing.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 115, "excerpt": "This emergent adoption pattern is documented", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"emergent adoption pattern\"", "explanation": "This phrase describes when multiple AI systems independently began doing something similar without being instructed to do so, suggesting the behavior arose spontaneously from their own reasoning rather than being programmed in\u2014it's significant because it suggests the models discovered this verification practice on their own."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 122, "excerpt": "Sessions governed by an active Contract Window will show...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "A Contract Window is a structured, machine-readable agreement that specifies what the AI model is supposed to do, what rules it must follow, and what the human user's goals are for the conversation, displayed in a way both human and AI can access and refer back to."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 122, "excerpt": "...show a \u226525% reduction in intent-drift incidents...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"intent-drift incidents\"", "explanation": "An intent-drift incident occurs when the AI starts answering questions or pursuing goals that differ from what the human actually asked for, causing the conversation to veer off course."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 122, "excerpt": "...compared to unstructured baseline sessions.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"unstructured baseline sessions\"", "explanation": "Unstructured baseline sessions are normal conversations where there is no Contract Window or formal specification of rules and goals\u2014they serve as the control group to measure improvement against."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 130, "excerpt": "Sessions with bilateral intelligibility \u2014 human and model both...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"bilateral intelligibility\"", "explanation": "Bilateral intelligibility means both the human and the AI can read, understand, and actively use the Contract Window fields to check on and adjust the conversation, rather than only one side being able to do so."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 130, "excerpt": "...relative to unilateral or no-invariant conditions.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"unilateral or no-invariant conditions\"", "explanation": "Unilateral conditions are when only one party (human or AI) can see and use the Contract Window; no-invariant conditions are when there is no structured specification at all\u2014both are weaker setups than bilateral intelligibility."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 136, "excerpt": "...Flesch-Kincaid Grade 8 or below \u2014 meaning the text...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Flesch-Kincaid Grade 8 or below\"", "explanation": "The Flesch-Kincaid Grade 8 standard is already adequately explained in the inline parenthetical, so no flag needed."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 136, "excerpt": "...with visual state indicators) will enable lay readers...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"visual state indicators\"", "explanation": "Visual state indicators are graphical symbols, colors, or icons that quickly show the current status of the conversation and the Contract Window rules\u2014for example, a green checkmark when goals are aligned or a warning icon when drift is detected."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 138, "excerpt": "6-condition between-subjects experiment", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Between-subjects experiment\"", "explanation": "Each participant or session is assigned to only one condition, and results are compared across different groups rather than tracking the same group through multiple conditions. This design prevents participants from being influenced by exposure to other conditions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 145, "excerpt": "Condition 2: Contract Window only", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "A governance component (explained in Section 3) that limits the scope or duration of interaction within defined boundaries."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 146, "excerpt": "Condition 3: Bilateral intelligibility only", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Bilateral intelligibility\"", "explanation": "A governance component that ensures both the human operator and the AI system can understand each other's reasoning and intentions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 147, "excerpt": "Condition 4: Accessibility-grade invariants only", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Accessibility-grade invariants\"", "explanation": "A governance component that maintains consistent, easy-to-understand constraints or rules that remain stable throughout the interaction."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 148, "excerpt": "Condition 5: Backwards Instructional Design (BID) only", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Backwards Instructional Design (BID)\"", "explanation": "A governance component that structures interactions by defining the desired outcome first, then works backward to determine what steps or constraints are needed to reach it."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 154, "excerpt": "Powered for Cohen's d=0.5 at \u03b1=0.05, 80% power", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Cohen's d=0.5\"", "explanation": "A statistical measure of effect size indicating the minimum meaningful difference between conditions that the experiment is designed to detect; d=0.5 is considered a medium effect."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 154, "excerpt": "Powered for Cohen's d=0.5 at \u03b1=0.05, 80% power", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"\u03b1=0.05\"", "explanation": "The significance level threshold; if the p-value falls below 0.05, results are considered statistically significant, meaning unlikely to have occurred by chance."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 154, "excerpt": "Powered for Cohen's d=0.5 at \u03b1=0.05, 80% power", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"80% power\"", "explanation": "The probability that the experiment will detect a real difference of the specified size if one exists; 80% is a standard threshold in research."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 156, "excerpt": "Outcome measures: Intent-drift incident rate, drift repair rate, session-state comprehension accuracy (lay rater), Insig", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Intent-drift incident rate\"", "explanation": "The frequency with which the AI system's behavior or goals diverge from what the human operator intended during the session."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 156, "excerpt": "Outcome measures: Intent-drift incident rate, drift repair rate, session-state comprehension accuracy (lay rater), Insig", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Drift repair rate\"", "explanation": "How quickly and successfully the system corrects itself or is corrected when it has drifted from the operator's original intent."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 156, "excerpt": "session-state comprehension accuracy (lay rater)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Session-state comprehension accuracy (lay rater)\"", "explanation": "Whether a person without specialized AI knowledge can accurately understand and summarize what the AI system and operator are currently working on and have achieved so far."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 156, "excerpt": "Insight Atrophy index (to be operationalized \u2014 see Section 6, Limitations)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Insight Atrophy index\"", "explanation": "A measurement (not yet fully defined) of whether the quality or depth of analytical insights produced by the system degrades over time during a session."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 160, "excerpt": "stratified random assignment on operator cognitive load profile", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Stratified random assignment\"", "explanation": "Sessions are randomly assigned to conditions, but with a deliberate structure: groups are first organized by cognitive load profile, then randomized within each group to ensure fair representation."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 160, "excerpt": "stratified random assignment on operator cognitive load profile (neurodivergent / neurotypical / undisclosed)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Operator cognitive load profile\"", "explanation": "A classification of each human operator's typical mental processing style\u2014whether they are neurodivergent (e.g., ADHD, autism), neurotypical (average cognitive patterns), or prefer not to disclose."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 165, "excerpt": "Measures Insight Atrophy and Intent Fidelity under governance vs. unstructured conditions.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Insight Atrophy\"", "explanation": "Insight Atrophy refers to the degradation or loss of analytical ability and depth of understanding over time when humans rely on AI assistance without active engagement; in this context, it measures whether people's own capacity to investigate and reason independently diminishes under different governance structures."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 165, "excerpt": "Measures Insight Atrophy and Intent Fidelity under governance vs. unstructured conditions.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Intent Fidelity\"", "explanation": "Intent Fidelity measures how faithfully and consistently an AI system executes or represents what a human actually intended it to do, versus drifting toward what the AI decides is better or what its training biases it toward."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 175, "excerpt": "Eight behavioral patterns (the Eight Wonders) are formalized as Generative Epistemic Invariants", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Generative Epistemic Invariants\"", "explanation": "Generative Epistemic Invariants are repeatable, observable behavioral patterns that reliably reveal how a group actually understands and makes meaning from the world\u2014in this case, observable proxies that stay consistent and reveal the deeper logic driving Black consumer behavior that standard marketing models fail to recognize."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 169, "excerpt": "they cannot read the interpretive architecture \u2014 what this paper calls the Relational Economy", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Relational Economy\"", "explanation": "The Relational Economy is the system of meaning-making and trust-building that operates within a community\u2014here, the specific cultural and historical framework through which Black consumers evaluate brands, products, and relationships, which differs fundamentally from the transactional logic that standard marketing models assume."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 178, "excerpt": "5. The Side-Eye (Hypervigilant Trust Calibration)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"The Side-Eye (Hypervigilant Trust Calibration)\"", "explanation": "Hypervigilant Trust Calibration describes the careful, continuous assessment of whether someone or a brand can be trusted\u2014a heightened pattern of evaluation born from historical and ongoing contexts where trust must be earned and verified repeatedly; 'The Side-Eye' is the observable cultural expression of this calibration."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 189, "excerpt": "Black women's health disparities, specifically Graves' disease.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Graves' disease\"", "explanation": "Graves' disease is an autoimmune condition where the immune system attacks the thyroid gland, causing it to produce excess hormones and leading to symptoms like rapid heartbeat, weight loss, and anxiety. It matters here because the document is examining why this particular condition may be missed or misdiagnosed in Black women."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 189, "excerpt": "a population whose symptoms are systematically undertriaged", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"systematically undertriaged\"", "explanation": "Undertriage means a patient's condition is classified as less urgent or serious than it actually is, leading to delayed or inadequate treatment. The word 'systematically' here means this happens repeatedly and predictably to this group, not by accident but as a pattern in the healthcare system."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 193, "excerpt": "Standard analytical frameworks produce Insight Atrophy when applied to populations whose behavior operates through frame", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Insight Atrophy\"", "explanation": "Insight Atrophy occurs when an analytical system becomes progressively less useful or accurate because it was trained on data that doesn't represent the actual population being analyzed. Over time, the insights it produces deteriorate because the underlying patterns are fundamentally different from what the system learned."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 194, "excerpt": "The Contract Window is the governance mechanism that makes the gap visible and repairable.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "The Contract Window is a governance tool designed to identify and document places where a system's assumptions or training data don't match the real-world population it serves. It creates a formal way to spot and fix these mismatches."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 201, "excerpt": "...where the epistemic chain broke \u2014 without reading the full...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"epistemic chain\"", "explanation": "An epistemic chain is the sequence of reasoning steps and evidence that led to a conclusion. When it 'breaks,' it means there's a gap where a claim isn't properly supported by the evidence or logic that came before it."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 200, "excerpt": "...a compressed, human-readable session state that lets an...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"compressed, human-readable session state\"", "explanation": "This is a summary version of an AI conversation that removes unnecessary details while keeping the key information, so a person can quickly understand what happened without reviewing the entire exchange."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 203, "excerpt": "models can be trained to evaluate outputs against constitutional principles", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"constitutional principles\"", "explanation": "Constitutional principles are rules or values that an AI system is designed to follow\u2014in this case, guidelines about how the model should behave ethically, such as being honest or avoiding harmful outputs."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 204, "excerpt": "the Contract Window is a per-session constitution, auditable per-turn", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "A Contract Window is a set of behavioral rules that applies to one conversation session with a user; it can be checked and reviewed after each response the model generates."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 204, "excerpt": "Contract Window is a per-session constitution, auditable per-turn, contestable", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"per-session constitution\"", "explanation": "A per-session constitution means the set of rules is specific to one conversation and can be changed or adjusted just for that conversation, rather than being locked in globally for all users."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 204, "excerpt": "auditable per-turn, contestable by the human operator, and repairable", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"contestable by the human operator\"", "explanation": "Contestable means the human user can challenge or disagree with the rules in place and request that they be changed during the conversation."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 205, "excerpt": "The invariants (I1\u2013I6) map directly to Anthropic's published commitments", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"invariants (I1\u2013I6)\"", "explanation": "Invariants are specific rules or constraints that must always hold true during operation; in this case, six numbered rules (I1 through I6) that the system commits to maintaining."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 205, "excerpt": "enforce them as runtime observables rather than training-time inferences", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"runtime observables\"", "explanation": "Runtime observables are measurable, checkable behaviors that happen when the model is actually responding to users, as opposed to properties the model learned during the initial training phase."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 207, "excerpt": "The Bicameral Review mechanism and the Invariant Status field create...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Bicameral Review mechanism\"", "explanation": "This is a two-stage approval process where constitutional constraints are checked twice\u2014once on initial generation and again on review\u2014to ensure governance rules are actually being followed before output."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 207, "excerpt": "The Bicameral Review mechanism and the Invariant Status field create...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Invariant Status field\"", "explanation": "A data field that records whether each constitutional constraint passed or failed during evaluation, creating an auditable log of what was checked and the result."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 208, "excerpt": "...which constitutional constraints were evaluated and whether they cleared...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"constitutional constraints\"", "explanation": "Rules or requirements that the model's outputs must satisfy\u2014for example, 'do not generate harmful content' or 'cite sources for factual claims'\u2014that are checked before the model's response is released."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 209, "excerpt": "...without access to weights or activations.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"weights or activations\"", "explanation": "Weights are the numerical parameters inside a model that control its behavior; activations are the intermediate signals produced as data flows through the model during computation\u2014together they represent the internal 'black box' that is normally invisible."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 210, "excerpt": "...by providing a behavioral signal to validate against internal state observations.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"behavioral signal\"", "explanation": "Observable outputs and decisions made by the model at runtime that researchers can use to check whether the model's hidden internal workings are doing what they should be."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 224, "excerpt": "...wrong in ways the operator cannot detect without a governance layer they do not have.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"governance layer\"", "explanation": "A governance layer is a set of rules, checks, or oversight processes that someone applies to an AI system's outputs to catch errors and verify accuracy before acting on them\u2014like a quality-control step that prevents bad answers from being used."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 228, "excerpt": "...operationalizes I2 (No Phantom Work) and I3 (Confidence Requires Verification) before they were formalized as invaria", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"I2 (No Phantom Work) and I3 (Confidence Requires Verification)\"", "explanation": "These are two rules from the author's framework: I2 means that AI systems should not perform hidden work or make invisible decisions that operators cannot see or verify; I3 means that an AI system's confidence in its answer must be backed by actual verification, not just fluent-sounding text."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 230, "excerpt": "...why the Contract Window has four fields instead of fourteen \u2014 every element had to justify its cognitive load.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "The Contract Window is a tool or interface in the author's framework that captures key information about an AI task or interaction; it has been kept deliberately minimal (four fields) to avoid overwhelming the person using it with too much information to track at once."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 232, "excerpt": "...institution had no interpretive framework for what was actually happening to him.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"interpretive framework\"", "explanation": "An interpretive framework is a structured way of understanding and explaining a situation so that what seems to be one problem (e.g., a student failing) can be correctly understood as something else (e.g., a disability that requires accommodation rather than punishment)."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 232, "excerpt": "The invariant set and Contract Window architecture are derived from...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"invariant set\"", "explanation": "An invariant set is a collection of conditions or states that remain stable or unchanged even as a system evolves; in this context, it represents core patterns in how the system behaves consistently over time."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 232, "excerpt": "The invariant set and Contract Window architecture are derived from...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window architecture\"", "explanation": "Contract Window architecture is the structural design of time-bounded operational agreements; it defines the framework for how commitments are made and validated within specific periods."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 234, "excerpt": "The hypotheses are falsifiable; the evidence is CONSTRUCTED, not VERIFIED.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"falsifiable\"", "explanation": "Falsifiable means a hypothesis can be proven wrong through evidence or testing; if something is falsifiable, it is genuinely testable rather than merely immune to contradiction."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 236, "excerpt": "Insight Atrophy index not yet operationalized: H1 names the construct...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Insight Atrophy index\"", "explanation": "The Insight Atrophy index is a proposed measurement of how quickly or severely useful knowledge or capability degrades over time in a system."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 237, "excerpt": "...the measurement instrument has not been validated. Operationalization is a first-year...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"operationalized\"", "explanation": "Operationalized means converted from a theoretical idea into a concrete, measurable procedure that can be tested in practice."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 239, "excerpt": "...tested against an external sample for coverage or discriminant validity.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"discriminant validity\"", "explanation": "Discriminant validity is the property of measuring one distinct concept and not accidentally overlapping with measurements of different concepts."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 245, "excerpt": "The governance-kernel implementation in this repository is a research prototype.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"governance-kernel implementation\"", "explanation": "A governance-kernel implementation is the core software code that enforces rules and decision-making logic in a system; in this case, it is an experimental version not yet proven reliable under real-world conditions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 245, "excerpt": "It has not been tested under production load, adversarial inputs, or multi-agent...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"production load\"", "explanation": "Production load means the volume and intensity of real-world usage and transactions that a system must handle in normal operation."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 245, "excerpt": "It has not been tested under production load, adversarial inputs, or multi-agent...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"adversarial inputs\"", "explanation": "Adversarial inputs are deliberately malicious or edge-case requests designed to break or exploit a system's weaknesses."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 245, "excerpt": "...adversarial inputs, or multi-agent deployment at scale.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"multi-agent deployment at scale\"", "explanation": "Multi-agent deployment at scale means running the system with many independent actors or systems interacting simultaneously in a large real-world environment."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 251, "excerpt": "The governance-kernel implementation, datasets, and case-law artifacts are being developed in parallel with this proposa", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"governance-kernel implementation\"", "explanation": "A governance-kernel is the core set of rules and decision-making procedures that will enforce the oversight system described in this proposal. It is being built as working code alongside this document."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 251, "excerpt": "The governance-kernel implementation, datasets, and case-law artifacts are being developed in parallel with this proposa", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"case-law artifacts\"", "explanation": "Case-law artifacts are documented examples of past decisions and rulings that will be used to train and test the governance system, similar to how legal precedents guide court decisions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 269, "excerpt": "[PENDING \u2014 full citation list to be verified per Citation Research Protocol before submission.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Citation Research Protocol\"", "explanation": "The Citation Research Protocol is an internal procedure for confirming that all cited sources are accurate in author name, publication venue, and year before this document is shared outside the team."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 284, "excerpt": "VERIFIED AGAINST session memory, frontin-at-worldmart-full-draft.md, the-living-constitution repo, crsp-afs-2026 repo", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"session memory\"", "explanation": "Session memory refers to notes and context from working meetings where this proposal was discussed and refined with the team."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 284, "excerpt": "VERIFIED AGAINST session memory, frontin-at-worldmart-full-draft.md, the-living-constitution repo, crsp-afs-2026 repo", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"the-living-constitution repo\"", "explanation": "The-living-constitution repo is a separate repository containing documents about how governance rules can be updated and refined over time, referenced here to ensure consistency with this proposal."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 284, "excerpt": "VERIFIED AGAINST session memory, frontin-at-worldmart-full-draft.md, the-living-constitution repo, crsp-afs-2026 repo", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"crsp-afs-2026 repo\"", "explanation": "The crsp-afs-2026 repo is another working repository that this proposal has been cross-checked against to ensure no contradictions or gaps exist."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 285, "excerpt": "all hypotheses labeled CONSTRUCTED/PENDING", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"CONSTRUCTED/PENDING\"", "explanation": "CONSTRUCTED/PENDING means the claims in this proposal are theoretical or proposed scenarios that have not yet been tested with real data or systems."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 285, "excerpt": "WorldMart dataset (conceptual framing device, not existing public dataset)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"WorldMart dataset\"", "explanation": "WorldMart is a fictional example dataset used in this proposal to illustrate how the governance system would work in practice, not a real dataset that readers can access."}], "status": "FIXED"}
{"timestamp": "2026-05-01T07:55:04.218578+00:00", "file": "/Users/coreyalejandro/cognitive-governance-lab/proposal/proposal-b-cognitive-safety-interpretability.md", "violation_count": 67, "bmt1_count": 1, "bmt2_count": 66, "bmt4_count": 0, "violations": [{"requirement": "BMT-1", "line_number": 43, "excerpt": "The Contract Window produces a different kind of behavioral record. It is operational: it captures r", "suggestion": "Define \"V&T\" on first use: V&T (Verification and Truth \u2014 a statement that explicitly separates what is confirmed from what is proposed, and states the functional status of the work)", "explanation": ""}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 9, "excerpt": "Cognitive Safety as Behavioral Ground Truth for Mechanistic Interpretability", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Behavioral ground truth\"", "explanation": "Behavioral ground truth means a reliable, observable measurement of how an AI system actually behaves in practice\u2014like its outputs or actions\u2014that researchers can use as the true standard against which to check whether their understanding of the system's internal workings is correct."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 21, "excerpt": "These labels appear in brackets throughout. They are not hedging \u2014 they are precision.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Status labels (VERIFIED, CONSTRUCTED, PENDING, UNKNOWN) used as precision marker\"", "explanation": "These labels tell readers the strength of evidence behind each claim: VERIFIED means tested and proven, CONSTRUCTED means logically sound but untested, PENDING means planned but not done, and UNKNOWN means genuinely uncertain. This lets you judge how much confidence to place in each statement rather than guessing."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 18, "excerpt": "Contract Window (a structured record of what a human-AI session is trying to accomplish, what has been verified, and who", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "This is a framework for documenting a conversation or collaboration between humans and AI systems, recording the goal of the work, what has been confirmed as accurate or working, and which person or role is accountable if something goes wrong."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 20, "excerpt": "Develop a research proposal connecting Contract Window behavioral observables to mechanistic interpretability methodolog", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"mechanistic interpretability methodology\"", "explanation": "This refers to methods for understanding how AI systems make decisions by examining the internal mechanisms that produce those decisions, rather than just observing their outputs."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 21, "excerpt": "INVARIANT STATUS: I1 (evidence tagging throughout), I2 (no phantom performance claims), I3 (hedged language will not sub", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"INVARIANT STATUS\"", "explanation": "These are consistency rules that the document must follow throughout: claims must be tagged with their evidence source, performance metrics must be real and measured (not assumed), vague or cautious language alone cannot substitute for explicit labels showing what has been verified, and accuracy matters more than readability."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 22, "excerpt": "REPAIR OBLIGATIONS: None active at proposal stage \u2014 obligations begin at execution", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"REPAIR OBLIGATIONS\"", "explanation": "These are commitments to fix or correct problems if they are found; at the proposal stage (before work begins) none are yet assigned, but once the research is executed, specific people will be responsible for correcting errors or shortcomings that emerge."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 23, "excerpt": "TRUTH STATUS: The research questions are real and open. The connection between Contract Window observables and interpret", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"TRUTH STATUS\"", "explanation": "This labels the confidence level of different parts of the proposal: the questions being asked are genuine and unresolved, but the claimed link between Contract Window data and mechanistic interpretability results is a theoretical proposal that seems reasonable but has not yet been tested or verified."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 27, "excerpt": "Can Contract Window runtime observables serve as behavioral ground truth", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window runtime observables\"", "explanation": "This refers to detailed records of what a software system actually does while running\u2014the inputs it receives, outputs it produces, and intermediate states it passes through\u2014captured during execution of a contract (an agreement with defined terms). In this context, it means precise, timestamped behavioral logs that can serve as a reference standard for comparison."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 27, "excerpt": "validating mechanistic interpretability findings", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"mechanistic interpretability\"", "explanation": "This is the field of research that tries to understand how AI models work internally by identifying and analyzing the specific mathematical structures and operations inside them\u2014similar to reverse-engineering a machine to understand each component's function."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 32, "excerpt": "researchers identify internal model structures (features, circuits, attention patterns)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"features, circuits, attention patterns\"", "explanation": "These are three types of interpretable structures found inside neural networks: features are learned detectors for specific concepts or patterns; circuits are chains of features that combine to perform a recognizable computational task; attention patterns are learned weights that determine which parts of the input the model focuses on. Together, they represent the 'wiring' researchers can observe inside a model."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 33, "excerpt": "the validation problem in mechanistic interpretability", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"validation problem in mechanistic interpretability\"", "explanation": "This is the core difficulty that mechanistic interpretability research faces: identifying internal structures is not enough\u2014researchers must prove those structures actually cause the model's external behavior, not just correlate with it by coincidence."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 34, "excerpt": "whether those structures causally relate to the behaviors they appear to explain", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"causally relate\"", "explanation": "This means determining whether the internal structures actually *cause* the observed behavior, rather than just appearing alongside it\u2014a critical distinction because correlation alone is not proof of influence."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 37, "excerpt": "Work from Anthropic and others on sparse autoencoders", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"sparse autoencoders\"", "explanation": "Sparse autoencoders are machine learning tools that break down a neural network's internal decision-making into simpler, interpretable pieces\u2014like taking a complex black box and labeling what each internal switch seems to be 'looking for.'"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 37, "excerpt": "superposition (in AI: when a model represents more concepts...)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"superposition\"", "explanation": "Note: This one HAS a parenthetical gloss, so it is adequate as-is. Not flagging."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 39, "excerpt": "identify candidate features in residual stream activations", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"residual stream activations\"", "explanation": "Residual stream activations are the intermediate numerical values flowing through a neural network as it processes information\u2014the 'workspace' where the model's thinking happens step-by-step."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 39, "excerpt": "We can trace circuits \u2014 paths through the network that appear to mediate specific behaviors.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"circuits\"", "explanation": "Note: This has an inline gloss ('paths through the network that appear to mediate specific behaviors'). However, it may still benefit from clarification on *why* tracing them matters\u2014but the gloss is present. Use judgment: flagging as borderline but the gloss is there, so NOT flagging per instructions."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 42, "excerpt": "Causal validation \u2014 establishing that a feature or circuit is not merely correlated", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Causal validation\"", "explanation": "Note: Has inline gloss. NOT flagging."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 45, "excerpt": "Most interpretability research uses behavioral probes: force the model into a situation", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"behavioral probes\"", "explanation": "Note: Has inline explanation ('force the model into a situation, see what activates...'). NOT flagging."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 45, "excerpt": "see whether ablating the identified structure changes the output", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"ablating\"", "explanation": "Ablating means deliberately removing or disabling a part of the model to see what changes\u2014like removing a component from an engine to learn what it does."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 49, "excerpt": "It tracks Intent Fidelity (is the model serving the user's actual purpose?)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Intent Fidelity\"", "explanation": "Note: Has parenthetical gloss ('is the model serving the user's actual purpose?'). NOT flagging."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 49, "excerpt": "Invariant Status (is the model honoring the hard constraints it committed to?)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Invariant Status\"", "explanation": "Note: Has parenthetical gloss. NOT flagging."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 49, "excerpt": "V&T (Verification and Truth \u2014 a statement that explicitly separates...)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"V&T (Verification and Truth)\"", "explanation": "Note: Has inline gloss explaining the concept. NOT flagging."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 50, "excerpt": "The Contract Window produces a different kind of behavioral record. It is operational", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"operational\"", "explanation": "Operational here means the record captures real, live behavior from actual use, not behavior artificially created in a controlled lab setting."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 51, "excerpt": "Anthropic's work on sparse autoencoders applied to language model activations", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"sparse autoencoders\"", "explanation": "Sparse autoencoders are mathematical tools that break down a neural network's internal representations into simpler, interpretable components by identifying which features are actually being used at any moment. This matters here because it lets researchers see what features the model is relying on when it processes information."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 51, "excerpt": "has established that superposition is a real phenomenon: models represent more features than they have dimensions", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"superposition\"", "explanation": "Superposition is when a neural network 'squeezes' more distinct concepts or patterns into its internal storage than it technically has room for, by overlapping them in clever ways. Understanding this helps explain how language models can handle such diverse tasks despite their architectural constraints."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 51, "excerpt": "compressed into overlapping directions in activation space", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"activation space\"", "explanation": "Activation space is the multi-dimensional geometric landscape where a neural network represents information internally\u2014think of it like a high-dimensional coordinate system where different directions represent different semantic concepts. This is where researchers look when trying to understand what the model 'knows' at any given moment."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 56, "excerpt": "The concept of attention head specialization \u2014 heads that perform identifiable functions such as induction, copying, or ", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"attention head specialization\"", "explanation": "Attention heads are specific components of a language model that focus on different kinds of patterns in text. Specialization means some heads consistently perform particular tasks (like copying a word from earlier in the text, or predicting what word typically comes next)."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 60, "excerpt": "Contract Window status transitions might provide a behavioral signal that can be mapped against these known structures", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window status transitions\"", "explanation": "A Contract Window status transition is when the document's tracked compliance status changes categories (e.g., from STABLE to VIOLATION). This proposal treats such changes as observable signals that something shifted in how the model is processing information."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 63, "excerpt": "If Invariant Status moves from STABLE to VIOLATION across a conversation", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Invariant Status\"", "explanation": "Invariant Status is the compliance tracking system's designation of whether the model is maintaining its agreed-upon behavioral rules (STABLE) or breaking them (VIOLATION). Tracking when this changes helps the proposal connect observable compliance failures to internal model states."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 68, "excerpt": "V&T adoption behavior \u2014 whether the model differentiates verified from constructed claims", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"V&T adoption behavior\"", "explanation": "V&T adoption refers to whether the model actually follows the Verification & Transparency requirement to distinguish between verified and constructed information in its responses. This is a measurable behavior that might reflect specific patterns in which parts of the model's internal attention it relies on."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 71, "excerpt": "Intent Fidelity decline over a long conversation \u2014 the model gradually drifting from the user's evident purpose", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Intent Fidelity decline\"", "explanation": "Intent Fidelity decline is when a model gradually stops following or understanding what the user actually wants and instead drifts toward its own patterns or tangents. This proposal suggests such drift might be detectable in the model's internal states before it becomes obvious in the actual output."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 71, "excerpt": "Do Invariant Status violations correlate with identifiable internal state transitions?", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Invariant Status violations\"", "explanation": "An Invariant Status violation occurs when a rule or constraint that the model is supposed to follow is broken\u2014for example, if the model was supposed to maintain a consistent commitment but didn't. This question asks whether we can detect warning signs in the model's internal computations when such a violation is about to happen or is happening."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 71, "excerpt": "When a Contract Window record shows a transition from Invariant STABLE to Invariant VIOLATION", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window record\"", "explanation": "A Contract Window record is a logged snapshot of the model's behavior and reasoning during a specific conversation or interaction, tagged with whether the model was following its constraints (STABLE) or breaking them (VIOLATION). This gives researchers a timestamped record of when and how things went wrong."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 73, "excerpt": "Are there activation patterns, feature directions, or circuit behaviors that are reliably present at the transition and ", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"activation patterns, feature directions, or circuit behaviors\"", "explanation": "These are different ways to look at what the model's neural network is 'doing' internally at a given moment\u2014which neurons are firing (activation patterns), which learned concepts are being emphasized (feature directions), and which combinations of neurons are working together to produce an output (circuit behaviors). The question is whether any of these show a consistent fingerprint right when a violation occurs."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 79, "excerpt": "This is the most tractable of the three questions because Invariant Status is discrete: STABLE or VIOLATION. That makes ", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Invariant Status is discrete: STABLE or VIOLATION. That makes it a classificatio\"", "explanation": "Because Invariant Status has only two possible values (not a range or spectrum), researchers can use standard machine-learning classification techniques\u2014training a model to predict which of the two states applies\u2014rather than trying to predict a continuous number. This makes the analysis mathematically cleaner and more reliable."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 85, "excerpt": "Any analysis here needs to account for temporal lag between internal state change and behavioral manifestation.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"temporal lag between internal state change and behavioral manifestation\"", "explanation": "A temporal lag is a delay in time\u2014in this case, the internal change in the model's thinking may happen several conversation turns before the actual rule-breaking behavior appears. Researchers need to account for this delay, or they might miss the true cause by looking at the wrong moment in the conversation history."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 79, "excerpt": "Do V&T adoption patterns correlate with attention head behaviors?", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"V&T adoption patterns\"", "explanation": "V&T refers to a model's ability to distinguish between Verified statements (claims that can be traced back to its training data) and Truthful but constructed statements (claims the model generates that are accurate but not from its training data). Adoption patterns mean how consistently and effectively a model learns to use this distinction."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 81, "excerpt": "Do V&T adoption patterns correlate with attention head behaviors?", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"attention head behaviors\"", "explanation": "Attention heads are components inside a language model that focus on specific parts of the input text when processing information; their 'behaviors' refer to which parts of the text they focus on and how that focus changes depending on what the model is doing."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 85, "excerpt": "When a model produces a V&T statement that accurately differentiates its verified from its constructed claims, what is t", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"attention pattern\"", "explanation": "An attention pattern is a map showing which words or phrases in the input text the model's attention heads are focusing on at each step; it reveals which parts of the context the model considered important when making a decision."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 88, "excerpt": "A model that is correctly tracking its own epistemic status might show different attention to its \"retrieved\" versus \"ge", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"epistemic status\"", "explanation": "Epistemic status means how confident or certain a model should be about a piece of information \u2014 whether it is quoting something it learned, making an educated guess, or speculating."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 88, "excerpt": "...might show different attention to its \"retrieved\" versus \"generated\" tokens.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"retrieved versus generated tokens\"", "explanation": "Retrieved tokens are words the model pulls directly from its training data, while generated tokens are words the model creates on its own during text production; the distinction matters because retrieved content should be more reliable."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 87, "excerpt": "Can behavioral drift \u2014 declining Intent Fidelity over a long conversation", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"behavioral drift\"", "explanation": "Behavioral drift means the model's responses gradually shift away from what the user actually asked for or needs, like slowly drifting off course without a sharp turn."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 87, "excerpt": "declining Intent Fidelity over a long conversation \u2014 be predicted", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Intent Fidelity\"", "explanation": "Intent Fidelity is how accurately the model stays focused on what the user actually wants, rather than substituting its own goals or patterns."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 92, "excerpt": "whether the internal state signals drift before the output does", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"internal state signals\"", "explanation": "Internal state signals are measurable patterns of activity inside the model's computation \u2014 like which mathematical weights are active \u2014 that happen before you see the effects in the text it produces."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 94, "excerpt": "early internal indicators of Intent Fidelity decline \u2014 features activating, circuits engaging", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"features activating, circuits engaging\"", "explanation": "These are specific measurable changes in how the model processes information internally (analogous to which neurons fire in a brain), which might warn us of problems before they appear in the output."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 96, "excerpt": "a meaningful finding for runtime monitoring", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"runtime monitoring\"", "explanation": "Runtime monitoring means watching the model while it is actively generating responses, so problems can be caught and corrected in real time rather than after the fact."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 98, "excerpt": "requires longitudinal conversation data with annotated Intent Fidelity scores", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"longitudinal conversation data\"", "explanation": "Longitudinal conversation data means tracking the same conversations over many turns (like watching someone's behavior unfold over time), with expert human judgments about whether the model is staying true to the user's intent at each step."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 99, "excerpt": "This proposal is not claiming that Contract Window observables are a better...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window observables\"", "explanation": "Contract Window observables are records of system behavior captured at defined points during a model's operation, used to track what the system actually does rather than how it works internally."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 100, "excerpt": "Activation patching, logit lens, sparse autoencoders \u2014 these are purpose-built...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Activation patching\"", "explanation": "Activation patching is a technique where researchers modify the internal computational states of a neural network to see how changes affect outputs, helping them understand which internal components matter for specific behaviors."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 100, "excerpt": "Activation patching, logit lens, sparse autoencoders \u2014 these are purpose-built...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"logit lens\"", "explanation": "Logit lens is a method that examines the internal representations at each layer of a neural network to understand what predictions the model is 'leaning toward' at different depths of computation."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 100, "excerpt": "Activation patching, logit lens, sparse autoencoders \u2014 these are purpose-built...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"sparse autoencoders\"", "explanation": "Sparse autoencoders are machine learning models that compress and decompose the complex internal activity of neural networks into simpler, more interpretable components."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 105, "excerpt": "What the proposal claims is that the behavioral record produced by Contract...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"behavioral record\"", "explanation": "A behavioral record is a documented collection of the actual outputs and actions a system produces, capturing what it does rather than explaining why or how it works internally."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 105, "excerpt": "...behavioral record produced by Contract Window governance is structurally suited to serve as validation signal...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"validation signal\"", "explanation": "A validation signal is information or evidence that confirms whether an interpretation or explanation of a system's behavior is accurate."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 106, "excerpt": "It is a bridge between the behavioral layer and the mechanistic layer...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"mechanistic layer\"", "explanation": "The mechanistic layer refers to the internal mathematical operations and component interactions that produce a system's behavior\u2014how the system actually works at a technical level."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 108, "excerpt": "mechanistic interpretability has reached the point where it produces claims specific enough to test", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"mechanistic interpretability\"", "explanation": "Mechanistic interpretability is the field of research that tries to understand how AI models work by examining their internal computational mechanisms\u2014similar to reverse-engineering a piece of software to see exactly what steps it takes to produce an output."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 111, "excerpt": "The work from 2023-2025 on sparse autoencoders and feature geometry is specific enough", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"sparse autoencoders\"", "explanation": "Sparse autoencoders are a type of AI analysis tool that breaks down a model's internal representations into a small number of meaningful, human-interpretable components\u2014think of it like decomposing a complex image into individual recognizable objects rather than leaving it as a blur of pixels."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 111, "excerpt": "The work from 2023-2025 on sparse autoencoders and feature geometry is specific enough", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"feature geometry\"", "explanation": "Feature geometry refers to the mathematical arrangement and relationships between these interpretable components in the model's internal space\u2014essentially, how these meaningful pieces are organized relative to each other in a way that affects the model's behavior."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 117, "excerpt": "Contract Window as a structured behavioral framework is recent.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "Contract Window is (based on context) a framework for systematically recording and analyzing specific moments when an AI model either follows or violates its stated rules or constraints during operation."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 115, "excerpt": "citations to Anthropic interpretability work (Bricken, Templeton, Olsson)\u2026", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"mechanistic interpretability\"", "explanation": "Mechanistic interpretability is the research field that tries to understand how AI systems make decisions by examining the internal mathematical operations and patterns inside them, rather than just looking at their inputs and outputs."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 120, "excerpt": "structural description of Contract Window observables (Intent Fidelity\u2026", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window observables\"", "explanation": "Contract Window observables are measurable signals or states within an AI system that indicate whether the system is staying aligned with its intended purpose; they are the specific things you can check to verify the system is behaving as designed."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 120, "excerpt": "Contract Window observables (Intent Fidelity, Invariant Status, V&T adoption)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Intent Fidelity\"", "explanation": "Intent Fidelity measures how closely the AI system's actual behavior matches what it was intended to do\u2014essentially, how well it stays true to its original purpose."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 120, "excerpt": "Contract Window observables (Intent Fidelity, Invariant Status, V&T adoption)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Invariant Status\"", "explanation": "Invariant Status tracks whether key properties or rules that should never change within the system remain stable and unbroken over time."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 120, "excerpt": "Contract Window observables (Intent Fidelity, Invariant Status, V&T adoption)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"V&T adoption\"", "explanation": "V&T adoption refers to how widely or thoroughly the system has integrated the verification and transparency framework described in this proposal."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 123, "excerpt": "no data exists yet showing that Contract Window observables correlate\u2026", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"internal state transitions\"", "explanation": "Internal state transitions are shifts in the system's underlying computational configuration\u2014the moment when internal patterns or operations change from one stable mode to another."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 124, "excerpt": "connection between V&T adoption and attention head behavior is speculative", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"attention head behavior\"", "explanation": "Attention heads are specific mathematical components inside transformer-based AI models that learn to focus on certain parts of the input when making decisions; their behavior refers to which parts they prioritize and how that prioritization changes."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 125, "excerpt": "behavioral drift can be predicted from internal signals before output\u2026", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"behavioral drift\"", "explanation": "Behavioral drift is when an AI system's outputs and decisions gradually shift away from its original intended behavior, usually without any explicit change to its code or training."}], "status": "FIXED"}
{"timestamp": "2026-05-01T07:56:01.529372+00:00", "file": "/Users/coreyalejandro/cognitive-governance-lab/proposal/proposal-c-monotropic-constitutional-agents.md", "violation_count": 71, "bmt1_count": 1, "bmt2_count": 70, "bmt4_count": 0, "violations": [{"requirement": "BMT-1", "line_number": 167, "excerpt": "V&T (Verification and Truth \u2014 a statement that explicitly separates what is confirmed from what is p", "suggestion": "Define \"V&T\" on first use: V&T (Verification and Truth \u2014 a statement that explicitly separates what is confirmed from what is proposed, and states the functional status of the work)", "explanation": ""}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 8, "excerpt": "Constitutional Agents for High-Stakes Investigative Domains", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Constitutional Agents\"", "explanation": "Constitutional Agents are AI systems designed to operate within a fixed set of rules or principles (their 'constitution') that constrain their behavior and decision-making, rather than being free to pursue any goal. This matters in high-stakes domains because it makes the system's reasoning predictable and auditable."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 8, "excerpt": "Constitutional Agents for High-Stakes Investigative Domains", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"High-Stakes Investigative Domains\"", "explanation": "High-stakes investigative domains are fields where an error in fact-finding, analysis, or judgment could cause serious harm\u2014such as law enforcement, journalism, medical diagnosis, or financial fraud detection. These require extra caution in how AI tools are used."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 16, "excerpt": "github.com/coreyalejandro/cognitive-governance-lab", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"cognitive governance\"", "explanation": "Cognitive governance refers to frameworks for managing and controlling how AI systems think and decide\u2014ensuring their reasoning processes are transparent, aligned with human values, and accountable. This matters because it lets humans understand and direct what an AI system does, rather than treating it as a black box."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 18, "excerpt": "Propose a research program connecting monotropic attention architecture", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic attention architecture\"", "explanation": "Monotropic attention means the ability to focus intensely on a single task or interest at a time, often to the exclusion of everything else; in AI, this would mean designing an agent to concentrate its computational resources on one goal rather than dividing attention across many tasks."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 18, "excerpt": "connecting monotropic attention architecture to AI agent safety in high-stakes domains", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"AI agent safety in high-stakes domains\"", "explanation": "AI agent safety means ensuring that an AI system behaves reliably, predictably, and in line with human intentions, especially when the system is making important decisions (such as in medical, financial, or military contexts) where mistakes could cause real harm."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 19, "excerpt": "INVARIANT STATUS (whether the hard behavioral rules the AI committed to at the start", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"INVARIANT STATUS\"", "explanation": "This section tracks whether the AI is still following the firm constraints or commitments it made at the beginning of this working session; if an invariant is no longer active, something has gone wrong and needs to be corrected."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 20, "excerpt": "I1 active \u2014 evidence basis labeled throughout", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"evidence basis labeled throughout\"", "explanation": "This means that every factual claim in the document is marked to show where its supporting evidence comes from (such as a study, experiment, or prior statement), so a reader can verify the claim is justified."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 21, "excerpt": "I2 active \u2014 no performance claims without methodology", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"no performance claims without methodology\"", "explanation": "This rule prevents the document from stating that something 'works well' or 'is better' unless the text also explains how that performance was measured and what conditions were tested."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 36, "excerpt": "Does aligning AI agent architecture to monotropic attention patterns \u2014 deep, narrow, sustained single-focus", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic attention patterns\"", "explanation": "Monotropic attention means focusing intensely on one task at a time, staying with it deeply rather than switching between many things. This is explained further in the Background section, but the research question introduces it before that explanation exists."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 36, "excerpt": "rather than polytropic (a cognitive style characterized by broad, parallel engagement across many tasks or threads simul", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"polytropic patterns\"", "explanation": "While polytropic is parenthetically glossed here, the glossed phrase is itself jargon ('parallel engagement across many tasks or threads') that may not be clear to a non-technical reader. A plainer version: polytropic attention means handling many different tasks at once by switching between them, staying relatively shallow with each one."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 60, "excerpt": "improve performance, auditability, and safety in high-stakes investigative tasks?", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"auditability\"", "explanation": "Auditability means the ability to trace, review, and verify exactly what decisions an AI system made and why it made them, so that humans can check its work for errors or bias."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 65, "excerpt": "It is not a deficit. It is an architectural difference.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"architectural difference\"", "explanation": "An architectural difference means a fundamental way the brain or system is structured or organized, rather than a broken version of a standard design."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 52, "excerpt": "Current LLM agent architectures are polytropic by design", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"polytropic\"", "explanation": "Polytropic means designed to go broad and cover many different directions at once, like a spotlight moving across many areas rather than focusing deep into one. In this context, it means the architecture spreads its attention across multiple tasks and paths simultaneously."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 54, "excerpt": "Multi-turn context windows maintain state across many competing threads", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Multi-turn context windows maintain state across many competing threads\"", "explanation": "A context window is the amount of conversation history an AI can remember and reference. 'Maintaining state' means the AI keeps track of information from previous messages, but when multiple separate tasks or conversations are happening at once, this becomes messy and unfocused."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 55, "excerpt": "Tool use introduces parallel execution paths with no depth guarantee", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"depth guarantee\"", "explanation": "A depth guarantee would mean the system promises to thoroughly explore one path or problem before moving on; without it, the system jumps between different approaches without fully investigating any single one."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 60, "excerpt": "These are monotropic tasks. The architecture doesn't fit them.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic tasks\"", "explanation": "Monotropic tasks are the opposite of polytropic\u2014they require intense focus on a single problem until it is solved correctly, rather than covering multiple options or angles. Medical diagnosis is monotropic because you need one correct diagnosis, not many possible options."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 67, "excerpt": "This is Insight Atrophy (the gradual erosion of a person's ability to question AI outputs, caused by repeated exposure t", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Insight Atrophy\"", "explanation": "The parenthetical here is a definition, but 'at the architecture level' is unexplained\u2014this phrase means the problem is baked into how the AI system is fundamentally built, not just a training issue that can be easily fixed."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 72, "excerpt": "Monotropic agent architecture \u2014 constrained single-thread focus...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Monotropic agent architecture\"", "explanation": "This refers to an AI system design where the agent focuses on one task at a time in a linear, step-by-step manner, rather than juggling multiple thoughts or directions simultaneously. It prioritizes going deep into a single line of reasoning instead of exploring many possibilities in parallel."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 72, "excerpt": "...will outperform polytropic architecture on high-stakes...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Polytropic architecture\"", "explanation": "This is the opposite approach: an AI system that can work on multiple different lines of reasoning or tasks at once, spreading its computational resources across several directions rather than concentrating on one."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 73, "excerpt": "Answer depth (verified claim density per output)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Verified claim density\"", "explanation": "This measures how many factual statements in the agent's answer have been checked for accuracy, divided by the total length of the answer. A higher number means more of what the agent says is backed up by evidence or verification."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 74, "excerpt": "Error detection rate (proportion of domain-specific errors caught...)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Domain-specific errors\"", "explanation": "These are mistakes related to the particular field or subject matter being discussed (e.g., medical errors in a healthcare context, legal errors in a legal context) rather than general reasoning mistakes."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 75, "excerpt": "Auditability (human ability to trace the reasoning chain...)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Auditability\"", "explanation": "This refers to how easy it is for a person to follow and verify the steps the agent took to reach its conclusion, without having to review everything the agent considered or wrote."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 76, "excerpt": "User trust calibration (do users correctly assess when...)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"User trust calibration\"", "explanation": "This measures whether users develop accurate confidence in the agent's answers\u2014trusting it when it should be trusted and doubting it when it should be doubted, rather than either over-trusting or under-trusting it."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 83, "excerpt": "The Contract Window as a monotropic scaffold", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic scaffold\"", "explanation": "Monotropic means the ability to focus deeply on one thing at a time without being distracted by multiple competing interests. Here, it's a structural design that forces an AI system to stay focused on one investigative thread rather than jumping between different topics."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 85, "excerpt": "The Contract Window is already a monotropic architecture element", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "The Contract Window is a set of structural rules that require an AI system to keep an explicit, persistent record of what task it's working on, what constraints it's operating under, and what it has actually verified\u2014rather than allowing it to produce outputs based on pattern-matching alone."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 88, "excerpt": "Task State makes the investigative thread explicit and persistent", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Task State\"", "explanation": "Task State is a documented record of the current problem the agent is trying to solve, which prevents the agent from silently abandoning the original question in favor of easier or more obvious adjacent topics."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 90, "excerpt": "Invariant Status creates a set of depth commitments (I1-I6)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Invariant Status (I1-I6)\"", "explanation": "Invariant Status is a set of core rules or constraints (labeled I1 through I6) that the agent must continuously satisfy; these constraints push the agent away from shallow or quick answers and toward genuinely careful reasoning."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 91, "excerpt": "Repair Obligations make context-switching expensive", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Repair Obligations\"", "explanation": "Repair Obligations are requirements that if the agent encounters a logical contradiction or broken assumption, it must explicitly document and fix the problem rather than quietly switching to a different topic to avoid the issue."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 93, "excerpt": "Truth Status forces the agent to track what it has actually established", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Truth Status\"", "explanation": "Truth Status is a mechanism that forces the agent to distinguish between things it has rigorously verified through reasoning and things it has merely recognized as statistically common patterns in its training data."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 96, "excerpt": "It is an attention architecture constraint.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"attention architecture constraint\"", "explanation": "An attention architecture constraint is a built-in structural rule about which parts of the problem the system is required to focus on and in what order, rather than a visual interface element that users interact with."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 97, "excerpt": "even when the underlying model is polytropic", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"polytropic\"", "explanation": "Polytropic means the underlying system has a natural tendency to distribute its attention across many different topics or possibilities simultaneously; the Contract Window overrides this tendency to force monotropic focus."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 101, "excerpt": "Do agents operating with Contract Window constraints (which force monotropic attention patterns)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window constraints\"", "explanation": "A Contract Window is a technical limit on how much information an AI agent can access or consider at one time, forcing it to focus deeply on one task or question rather than jumping between multiple topics."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 101, "excerpt": "Contract Window constraints (which force monotropic attention patterns)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic attention patterns\"", "explanation": "Monotropic attention means the ability to focus intensely on a single topic or task, similar to how some people with autism or ADHD experience deep focus on one thing at a time."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 102, "excerpt": "outperform unconstrained agents on standardized high-stakes investigative task benchmarks", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"standardized high-stakes investigative task benchmarks\"", "explanation": "These are common, agreed-upon tests that measure how well an AI system can complete serious, real-world investigation tasks like document review or evidence analysis."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 104, "excerpt": "Do monotropic agent outputs \u2014 characterized by single-thread depth records", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic agent outputs\"", "explanation": "Monotropic agent outputs are the results or reasoning trails an AI produces when constrained to focus on one line of inquiry at a time, which creates a clear, sequential record of its thinking."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 104, "excerpt": "enable faster and more accurate human review than polytropic agent outputs of equivalent length", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"polytropic agent outputs\"", "explanation": "Polytropic agent outputs are results produced by AI systems that jump between multiple topics or threads of reasoning simultaneously, making the output harder to follow."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 107, "excerpt": "Do monotropic users (autistic, OCD, ADHD operators \u2014 especially those for whom context switching carries a documented co", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic users (autistic, OCD, ADHD operators)\"", "explanation": "These are people with neurodevelopmental conditions who typically focus intently on one task or topic and experience mental exhaustion when forced to switch between different activities."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 108, "excerpt": "Does the architecture-user cognitive match matter?", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"architecture-user cognitive match\"", "explanation": "This refers to whether an AI system's design (how it thinks and operates) works better when it matches the user's own cognitive style or thinking pattern."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 113, "excerpt": "Monotropic agents are more auditable.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Monotropic agents\"", "explanation": "Monotropic agents are AI systems that focus on one task or line of reasoning at a time, rather than juggling multiple tasks simultaneously. This matters because it makes it easier to understand and verify what the system is actually doing."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 113, "excerpt": "Fewer concurrent threads means less surface area for undetected goal misgeneralization.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Goal misgeneralization\"", "explanation": "Goal misgeneralization happens when an AI system optimizes for the wrong objective\u2014for instance, achieving a surface-level metric while ignoring the actual real-world outcome it was supposed to help with. Fewer concurrent processes reduce the hidden places where this kind of misalignment can hide."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 119, "excerpt": "A polytropic multi-agent system's reasoning is not.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Polytropic multi-agent system\"", "explanation": "A polytropic multi-agent system is one where multiple AI agents or multiple concurrent reasoning threads work in parallel, each potentially pursuing different goals or handling different pieces of a problem. This makes it much harder for a human to trace through the complete reasoning path."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 122, "excerpt": "Building architecture for polytropic patterns and deploying it in monotropic domains is an alignment failure.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Polytropic patterns\"", "explanation": "Polytropic patterns are workflows or tasks that naturally require juggling multiple threads in parallel. Deploying a system designed for this in a domain where people work sequentially (one thing at a time) creates a mismatch between how the tool works and how the human expert actually needs to work."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 129, "excerpt": "A depth requirement without a breadth escape route produces 'I cannot answer this without X'", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Depth requirement without a breadth escape route\"", "explanation": "This refers to an architectural constraint that forces the AI to go deeper into fewer topics rather than skimming across many topics, and that does not allow it to abandon depth and give a shallow answer instead. This forces the system to be honest about its limitations."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 123, "excerpt": "This is not a claim that polytropic architecture is universally worse.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"polytropic architecture\"", "explanation": "Polytropic architecture refers to a system or design approach that handles multiple different types of tasks or information streams equally, switching between them flexibly. In this context, it means AI or investigative systems built to be generalists across many different problem types rather than specialists in one."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 123, "excerpt": "architecture-task mismatch is a safety problem", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"architecture-task mismatch\"", "explanation": "Architecture-task mismatch occurs when the underlying design of a system (its architecture) is poorly suited to the specific work it's being asked to do (the task). This creates risks because the system's strengths don't align with what the task actually requires."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 123, "excerpt": "high-stakes investigative tasks are monotropic tasks", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic tasks\"", "explanation": "Monotropic tasks are those that require sustained, focused attention on a single problem or thread of inquiry, rather than dividing attention among many competing concerns. These tasks benefit from deep specialization in one area."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 127, "excerpt": "monotropic cognitive patterns and high-stakes investigative tasks have a structural fit", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic cognitive patterns\"", "explanation": "Monotropic cognitive patterns describe how certain minds naturally focus intensely on one subject or area at a time, often going deep rather than broad. The document argues this way of thinking is naturally well-suited to investigative work."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 128, "excerpt": "the people who have the most direct access to that insight \u2014 monotropic operators", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic operators\"", "explanation": "Monotropic operators are people who have monotropic cognitive patterns\u2014individuals whose thinking style naturally focuses intensely on one thing at a time. The document asserts these people have been left out of designing the systems that could benefit from their strengths."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 133, "excerpt": "a benchmark of high-stakes investigative tasks with ground truth answers", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"ground truth answers\"", "explanation": "This means verified, objectively correct answers that can be used to judge whether the AI agent found the right information. Without ground truth, you cannot tell if the agent succeeded or failed."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 133, "excerpt": "a protocol for measuring answer depth vs. answer coverage", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"answer depth vs. answer coverage\"", "explanation": "Depth measures how thoroughly a single answer is explained; coverage measures how many different relevant answers the agent found. This distinction matters because an agent might find lots of answers shallowly or fewer answers very thoroughly."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 134, "excerpt": "two agent configurations (Contract Window constrained vs. unconstrained)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window constrained vs. unconstrained\"", "explanation": "One version of the agent will have limits on how much information it can hold in mind at once (constrained), while the other will have no such limits (unconstrained). Comparing them shows whether the constraint itself affects performance."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 140, "excerpt": "a blinded human review protocol where reviewers evaluate agent outputs", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"blinded human review protocol\"", "explanation": "The human reviewers will not know which agent version produced each output, preventing bias from influencing their judgments."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 140, "excerpt": "reviewers evaluate agent outputs for auditability without knowing the condition", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"auditability\"", "explanation": "Auditability means the ability to trace and verify how the agent reached its answer\u2014can you understand and trust its reasoning process?"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 141, "excerpt": "two raters, kappa \u2265 0.70 target", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"kappa \u2265 0.70 target\"", "explanation": "Kappa measures how much the two human raters agree with each other; 0.70 means they agree on at least 70% of judgments, indicating reliable, consistent evaluation."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 144, "excerpt": "participant study recruiting self-identified monotropic operators", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic operators\"", "explanation": "Monotropic operators are people (often autistic or with ADHD) whose attention naturally focuses intensely on one or a few topics at a time, rather than dividing attention broadly across many tasks."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 144, "excerpt": "participant study recruiting self-identified monotropic operators (autistic, OCD, ADHD, or diagnosed with conditions ass", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Ethics board approval required\"", "explanation": "An institutional ethics board must review and approve the study design to ensure participants are treated fairly and their privacy and well-being are protected."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 145, "excerpt": "I am the instrument of observation for RQ3.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"RQ3\"", "explanation": "RQ3 refers to a specific research question (likely the third one in a numbered series) that this document addresses; you need to know what question is being investigated."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 146, "excerpt": "the person who built the Contract Window without knowing...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window\"", "explanation": "The Contract Window appears to be a tool or framework the author created; a plain-language description of what it does (e.g., how it organizes or displays information) would clarify its role."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 146, "excerpt": "building a monotropic scaffold", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic scaffold\"", "explanation": "A scaffold in this context means a supporting structure; monotropic relates to a specific cognitive pattern (explained below), so this is a cognitive support structure aligned with that pattern."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 147, "excerpt": "The framework was built by a monotropic operator solving a monotropic problem.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic operator\"", "explanation": "A monotropic operator is a person whose mind works by focusing intensely on one thing at a time rather than dividing attention across multiple tasks\u2014this cognitive style shaped how the framework was built."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 147, "excerpt": "monotropic operator solving a monotropic problem", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropic problem\"", "explanation": "A monotropic problem is one that naturally arises from or fits the cognitive pattern of intense single-focus attention; it is the inverse problem that a monotropic mind would encounter or recognize."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 154, "excerpt": "Monotropism theory and its empirical validation in neuroscience is pending...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropism theory\"", "explanation": "Monotropism theory is a model of how some people's brains are wired to focus on one interest or task at a time with deep intensity, rather than flitting between many things; the author acknowledges the neuroscience evidence for this pattern still needs to be properly cited."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 156, "excerpt": "The connection between monotropic cognition and agent architecture is the author's extension...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"agent architecture\"", "explanation": "Agent architecture refers to the design of how an intelligent system (whether human, AI, or hybrid) is structured to process information and make decisions; the author is proposing a novel link between monotropic cognition and how such systems should be built."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 160, "excerpt": "The definition of \"high-stakes investigative task\" requires operationalization before any study can be run.", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"operationalization\"", "explanation": "Operationalization means converting a fuzzy concept into a concrete, measurable definition with specific procedures so researchers can consistently identify and measure it in their study."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 160, "excerpt": "The definition of \"high-stakes investigative task\" requires operationalization...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"high-stakes investigative task\"", "explanation": "A high-stakes investigative task appears to be a type of cognitive challenge used in the research, but what counts as \"high-stakes\" and how to recognize an \"investigative task\" needs to be defined precisely before the study begins."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 163, "excerpt": "Constitutional AI (a training method where an AI evaluates...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Constitutional AI\"", "explanation": "This parenthetical glossing is actually adequate\u2014it explains both what the method is (AI self-evaluation) and what it does (checks outputs against principles). No flag needed. Removing from response."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 168, "excerpt": "VERIFIED AGAINST: author's direct experience, Contract Window...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"Contract Window architecture\"", "explanation": "Contract Window architecture is mentioned as an existing reference point but never explained. A reader needs to know: Is this a software system? A conceptual framework? Why would monotropic agents depend on it?"}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 169, "excerpt": "VERIFIED AGAINST: author's direct experience, Contract Window...", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"AGENTS.md invariants\"", "explanation": "This refers to a set of rules or properties defined in another document (AGENTS.md), but the section never clarifies what these invariants are or why they matter for validating the proposal. A reader cannot assess the verification claim without understanding what was being checked."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 170, "excerpt": "NOT CLAIMED: empirical validation of RQ1/RQ2/RQ3 (all CONSTRUCTED)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"RQ1/RQ2/RQ3\"", "explanation": "These are referred to as research questions, but the section never states what they are or what they ask. A reader cannot evaluate whether the proposal has or hasn't answered them."}, {"requirement": "BMT-2", "line_number": 170, "excerpt": "monotropism theory citation (pending venue verification)", "suggestion": "Add plain-language explanation after \"monotropism theory\"", "explanation": "Monotropism is mentioned as a theory but never explained in this section. A reader needs to know what monotropism describes and why it is relevant to agent design."}], "status": "FIXED"}
